:: FlightPrep [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Preflight: reviewing materials"])>>

<div class="scenario-title">Crossfeed</div>
<div class="scenario-subtitle">A night twin scenario: KSAT to KELP</div>

It's Saturday evening in late March. Sunset in San Antonio was 7:41, and the last of it is draining out of the sky west of the field. You're a private pilot, multi and instrument rated, about 700 hours total with 140 of it in twins, and eight months into a three-way partnership on a 1978 Seneca II based at El Paso International. Sixty hours in type. You still grin a little every time you walk up to it.

Tonight is the ride home from your father's seventieth birthday. Your sister Elena is with you, and she has a 6:45 shift in the neonatal ICU tomorrow morning. You told her she'd be in her own bed by eleven, El Paso time. She believed you, because you're you.

Walt, the senior partner, had the airplane in San Antonio this week and airlined home this morning. It's waiting for you on the ramp at Mission Trail Aviation with his note in the fuel log. The flight is 430 nautical miles, almost all of it over the emptiest stretch of Texas there is, at night, under a new moon.

<strong>Review your materials before heading out to the airplane:</strong>

<div class="chart-disclaimer">Charts, weather data, frequencies, and performance figures in this scenario are from the period in which it was written and may no longer be current. Use the materials provided here, not current publications, as the scenario is designed around them.</div>

<<link "<span class=\"preflight-btn\">Weather Briefing</span>" "Preflight-Weather">><<set $readWeather to true>><</link>>
<<link "<span class=\"preflight-btn\">Flight Plan & Fuel Log</span>" "Preflight-FlightPlan">><<set $readFlightPlan to true>><</link>>
<<link "<span class=\"preflight-btn\">Aircraft & Systems</span>" "Preflight-Aircraft">><<set $readAircraft to true>><</link>>
<<link "<span class=\"preflight-btn\">Area Map</span>" "Preflight-Map">><<set $readMap to true>><</link>>

<<if $readWeather and $readFlightPlan and $readAircraft and $readMap>>
<hr>
You've been through everything. Elena is finishing a text to her charge nurse. Time to go flying.

<<link "<span class=\"preflight-btn\">☑ Begin Flight</span>" "Ramp_Arrival">><</link>>
<<elseif $readWeather or $readFlightPlan or $readAircraft or $readMap>>
<hr>
<em>You haven't looked at everything yet. The airplane has been in someone else's hands all week, and the route is a long one. Take your time.</em>

<<link "<span class=\"preflight-btn\">Begin Flight Anyway</span>" "Ramp_Arrival">><</link>>
<</if>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Preflight-Weather [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reviewed weather briefing"])>>
<strong>Standard Briefing, self-briefed 1930 CDT (0030Z)</strong>

<p><em>Synopsis:</em> Weak surface ridge over the Hill Country. A shield of high cirrus is spreading east off the upper trough over the Davis Mountains and will thicken over the western half of the route through the night. No convection. No icing below FL180 on the route. Surface winds light everywhere. Winds aloft westerly, strengthening overnight. New moon tonight.</p>

<div class="metar-block">METARs (0053Z)

KSAT 220053Z 14006KT 10SM FEW250 21/12 A3002 RMK AO2 SLP164
KJCT 220055Z AUTO 15005KT 10SM CLR 19/09 A3003 RMK AO2
KFST 220055Z AUTO 16007KT 10SM CLR 20/07 A3004 RMK AO2
KELP 220051Z 12004KT 10SM BKN250 19/06 A3005 RMK AO2 SLP135

KPEQ: no observation available (AWOS out of service, see NOTAMs)</div>

<div class="metar-block">TAFs

KSAT 212320Z 2200/2224 14006KT P6SM SCT250
  FM221000 16005KT P6SM SCT250
KELP 212320Z 2200/2224 13005KT P6SM BKN250
  FM220900 VRB03KT P6SM SCT250</div>

<div class="metar-block">Winds aloft (route, valid 00Z-06Z)

          9,000       12,000
KSAT-KJCT 2312+08     2418+04
KFST-KELP 2415+06     2522+02

Plan number at 10,000: about 240 at 15.</div>

<div class="metar-block">NOTAMs (route-relevant)

KPEQ  AWOS-3 OUT OF SERVICE
KPEQ  RWY 14/32 CLSD (rehabilitation)
KFST  none
KELP  none affecting arrivals</div>

<p><em>Your own read: the METARs west of Junction say CLR because the automated stations can't see a cirrus deck at 25,000. It's up there, and it's moving east. Between the new moon and that shield, the western half of this flight will be flown inside a bag. Ceiling and visibility are a non-issue. Light is the issue.</em></p>

<<link "← Back to preflight" "FlightPrep">><</link>>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Preflight-FlightPlan [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reviewed flight plan and fuel log"])>>
<strong>Filed IFR Flight Plan</strong>

<div class="flight-plan">Aircraft:    N7462C  Piper PA-34-200T Seneca II
Equipment:   /G
True AS:     158 KTAS (65% cruise)
Departure:   KSAT   0110Z (2010 CDT)
Route:       KSAT DCT KELP
Altitude:    10,000
Destination: KELP (El Paso Intl)
Alternate:   none required (KELP forecast VFR, 91.169)
Time enrte:  2:54
Fuel:        3:42 (74 gal aboard per totalizer, block 20 gph)
Souls:       2
Remarks:     PARTNERSHIP ACFT, FUEL LOG NOTE SEE BELOW</div>

<p>Your planning math, written on the kneeboard in the FBO: 74 aboard, 58 to get there at block burn, lands with 16 gallons. That's 48 minutes at cruise. Legal for IFR under 91.167 with room to spare.</p>

<strong>The fuel log</strong>

<p>The last page is Walt's handwriting, dated this morning:</p>

<div class="flight-plan">"Topped the LEFT after my leg Thursday. Right reads right at
half, should be close. Set the JPI to 74. Gas here is criminal,
$8.15. Square the rest up at home, it's $5.90 at the co-op.
Smooth ride home. - W"</div>

<p>So: left tank full at 46.5 usable, verified by eye at the filler neck during your preflight, fuel against the collar. Right tank claimed at about half, which would be 23. The right gauge sits somewhere between three-eighths and a half and moves when you rock the wing. Nothing is visible down the right filler neck but darkness. There is no calibrated dipstick for a Seneca wing, and the JPI totalizer reads what Walt told it: 74.0.</p>

<strong>En-route airports (planning row)</strong>

<table class="airport-table">
<tr><th>ID</th><th>Airport</th><th>Along route</th><th>Elev</th><th>Runway</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
<tr><td>KJCT</td><td>Kimble County (Junction)</td><td>89 nm</td><td>1,749</td><td>17/35, 5,004 ft</td><td>CTAF, fuel daytime</td></tr>
<tr><td>KFST</td><td>Fort Stockton-Pecos County</td><td>245 nm</td><td>3,011</td><td>12/30, 7,508 ft</td><td>ASOS 118.525, CTAF 122.8, 100LL 24-hr self-serve, RNAV 12/30 + VOR 12, unattended after 1700</td></tr>
<tr><td>KPEQ</td><td>Pecos Municipal</td><td>abeam 282 nm, 22 N</td><td>2,613</td><td>09/27, 5,953 ft open</td><td>AWOS OTS, RWY 14/32 closed (NOTAMs)</td></tr>
<tr><td>KINK</td><td>Winkler County (Wink)</td><td>abeam 274 nm, 51 N</td><td>2,822</td><td>13/31, 5,003 ft</td><td>Well off route</td></tr>
<tr><td>KELP</td><td>El Paso Intl</td><td>430 nm</td><td>3,962</td><td>26L 9,025 / 22 12,020 / 26R 5,499</td><td>ATIS 120.0, Tower 118.3, full ILS/RNAV inventory</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Elena's arithmetic is simpler than yours. Wheels up around 8:10, El Paso gives an hour back at the time-zone line, home by eleven Mountain time, asleep by 11:30, alarm at 5:15. She has already told you twice tonight that you are her favorite airline.</p>

<<link "← Back to the planning table" "FlightPrep">><</link>>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Preflight-Aircraft [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reviewed aircraft and systems"])>>
<strong>N7462C: 1978 Piper PA-34-200T Seneca II</strong>

<div class="aircraft-card">Powerplants:  Continental TSIO-360-E (left) / LTSIO-360-E (right)
              200 hp/side, turbocharged, counter-rotating props.
              No critical engine. Both are critical.
Props:        2-blade constant speed, full feathering. Feather by
              pulling the prop lever full aft THROUGH the detent.
              Centrifugal pins BLOCK feathering below about 800 RPM.
              NO unfeathering accumulators: in-flight unfeather
              requires the starter to rotate the engine until oil
              pressure pulls the blades out of feather.
Fuel:         93 gal usable (46.5/side). Interconnected cells in
              each wing act as one tank per side, one filler per
              side. Electric boost pump each side.
Selectors:    Each engine has one selector: ON / OFF / X-FEED.
              ON     = engine feeds from its OWN wing.
              X-FEED = engine feeds from the OPPOSITE wing.
              The selector belongs to the ENGINE. Crossfeed points
              that engine's straw at the other wing, nothing more.
              Intended use: extended single-engine flight, to burn
              fuel from the dead engine's side and keep the wings
              in balance. Takeoff and landing: selectors ON.
Monitor:      JPI EDM-760 twin engine monitor with fuel flow and
              totalizer. The totalizer counts total gallons against
              whatever number you program at startup. It does not
              know, and cannot know, which tank the fuel is in.
Speeds:       Vmc 66 KIAS (red radial). Vyse 89 KIAS (blue radial).
              Single-engine service ceiling 13,400 (the turbos).
Burn:         About 20-22 gph combined at 65%. Partnership block
              plan: 20 gph, and it usually comes in a shade under.</div>

<strong>Open squawks (partnership sheet, taped inside the logbook)</strong>

<div class="aircraft-card">1. Right engine fuel flow runs ~0.9 gph higher than left at
   matched power. Injector service scheduled at annual (April).
2. Right fuel quantity gauge sticky below 1/2, reads low
   intermittently. Sender on order.
3. Autopilot altitude hold hunts +/- 40 ft above 11,000. Live
   with it.</div>

<strong>Weight and balance tonight</strong>

<div class="aircraft-card">Empty weight:            3,043 lb
You:                       195 lb
Elena:                     140 lb
Bags (two soft, one cake): 55 lb
Fuel, 74 gal:              444 lb
Ramp weight:             3,877 lb   (MGW 4,570: 693 under)
CG within envelope at ramp and at landing weight.
Full fuel (93 gal) would be 3,991 lb. Also fine.</div>

<<link "← Back to your planning materials" "FlightPrep">><</link>>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Preflight-Map [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reviewed area map"])>>
<strong>Route overview: KSAT to KELP</strong>

<div class="sectional-container">
<img src="/scenarios/crossfeed/images/area_map.jpg" alt="Route overview map, San Antonio to El Paso direct, showing Junction, Sonora, Ozona, Fort Stockton, Pecos, and Wink along the route">
<div class="sectional-label">Route overview: KSAT direct KELP, 430 nm. Junction (89 nm), abeam Sonora (135), abeam Ozona (159), abeam Fort Stockton (245), abeam Pecos (282, 22 north), Wink (274, 51 north), El Paso (430). Terrain rises westbound from 800 ft at San Antonio to nearly 4,000 at El Paso.</div>
</div>

<strong>Minimum safe altitudes, your planning ladder (westbound)</strong>

<table class="airport-table">
<tr><th>Segment</th><th>Rough min safe</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
<tr><td>KSAT → Junction</td><td>4,500</td><td>Hill Country, towers</td></tr>
<tr><td>Junction → Ozona</td><td>5,500</td><td>Plateau edge, wind farms</td></tr>
<tr><td>Ozona → Fort Stockton</td><td>6,800</td><td>Mesas south of I-10</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fort Stockton → KELP</td><td>8,500</td><td>Davis Mountains south, Guadalupes north</td></tr>
</table>

<p>The route parallels Interstate 10 most of the way, which matters at night, because west of Junction the interstate is close to the only continuous string of light on the ground. Towns are forty minutes apart at highway speed. Ranches out there are measured in sections. Between Ozona and Fort Stockton the chart shows more windmill symbols than town names, and under a new moon with cirrus overhead, the ground will be a rumor.</p>

<p>Filed at 10,000: high enough for the whole ladder, low enough to skip the oxygen conversation.</p>

<<link "← Back to the preflight hub" "FlightPrep">><</link>>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Ramp_Arrival [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Opening: the ramp at Mission Trail"])>>
The Seneca sits nose-out on the east ramp with the last orange of the day behind it, and it looks exactly like what it is: the best thing three busy people ever bought together. Your walkaround is done. Oil good both sides, gear pins out, static wicks all present, left filler neck full to the collar. The right filler neck shows you nothing but the smell of avgas and a black hole where fuel might be.

Elena comes down the FBO steps carrying the cake box like it's a patient. "Dad cried twice," she says. "Twice. Don't tell him I told you." She stows the box behind the rear seat with surgical care and settles into the right front like she owns it. She has ridden with you since your student solo days in a rented 152, and she is the only passenger you've ever had who falls asleep during turbulence.

Walt's note is folded into the fuel log on your knee. Right at half, should be close. The right gauge needle sits between three-eighths and a half and stirs when the wind rocks the wing. The JPI says 74.0 aboard, because that's what Walt typed into it. Your kneeboard math says the trip needs 58 with 16 left over.

Inside, Manny at the line desk is apologetic and honest. The Jet A truck has a Falcon and then a King Air, both crews on the clock. "Full top-off, you're waiting forty-five minutes, maybe an hour. I could squirt a quick ten in one side right now before the King Air, if that does anything for you. No self-serve on this side of the field."

Elena checks her phone and says nothing at all about the time.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Fuel Order</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Top off both sides and wait it out. An hour on the ramp is cheaper than uncertainty over Ozona." "Ramp_Wait">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D1: chose to wait for a full top-off"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Take it as it sits. The totalizer says 74, the trip needs 58, and the right gauge is a known liar that reads low. You'll square the burn with crossfeed once you're level." "Ramp_AsIs">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D1: took the lopsided load as-is"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Have Manny put the quick ten in the right side now. That covers the claimed shortfall without losing the night to the fuel queue." "Ramp_Splash">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D1: quick partial fill on the right"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "D. Call Walt before you decide anything. He fueled it, he can tell you what's actually in the right tank." "Ramp_WaltCall">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D1: tried to reach Walt first"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Ramp_WaltCall [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Called Walt: voicemail"])>>
<<set $waltTexted to true>>
Four rings, then Walt's voicemail, which is him saying "It's Walt" followed by a beep with no further instructions. Saturday night. He and Rosa will be at the dance hall in Fabens with his phone in the truck.

You text instead: <em>Quick one. How much is actually in the right tank? Gauge and your note don't quite agree.</em> The message sits there, delivered, unread.

Manny leans out the line shack door and holds up a hand, five fingers spread. Five minutes until the Falcon needs him, and then the offer of a quick splash gets a lot more complicated.

Elena has her seatbelt on already. Through the windshield you can see her reading the checklist pocket like it's a menu.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: Same Question, Less Time</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Wait for the full top-off, both sides, however long the queue runs." "Ramp_Wait">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D1 retry: full top-off after all"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Go with what's aboard. Walt's note plus the totalizer is two sources against one sticky gauge." "Ramp_AsIs">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D1 retry: launched with the load as found"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Flag Manny down for the quick ten gallons in the right before the Falcon takes him." "Ramp_Splash">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D1 retry: took the quick splash"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Ramp_Wait [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Waiting on the fuel queue"])>>
You tell Manny you'll take the full service, both sides, whenever the truck frees up. He nods like a man who has delivered worse news. "Soon as the King Air's buttoned up. I'll come find you."

The Falcon drinks for twenty minutes. You and Elena sit in the pilot lounge under a muted basketball game. She puts her feet up on her overnight bag and watches you not watch the clock.

"So we're late," she says. "How late is late?"

"Airborne by nine, maybe a little after. Your door around eleven thirty, quarter to twelve."

"Okay." She looks at the game for a while. "You know I'd rather be tired than worried. I can sleep in report. I've done it standing up." A beat. "But if there's a version of this where I'm not tired <em>or</em> worried, I'd take that one."

The King Air taxis up at 8:35 and plugs into Manny's clipboard. Out the window, the avgas truck sits fat and idle in front of it, twenty steps from your airplane.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Wait, Renegotiated</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Hold your place for the full top-off. The plan is the plan, and it's already paid for in waiting." "Ramp_TopOff">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Held for the full top-off"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Downgrade the order: ten quick gallons in the right side now, and you're gone before the King Air is done." "Ramp_Splash">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Downgraded to a quick splash"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Cancel the fuel order entirely. The math worked an hour ago and it works now, and the clock is the thing actually moving against you." "Ramp_AsIs">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Cancelled fuel, went as found"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Ramp_TopOff [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Topped off both sides"])>>
<<set $toppedOff to true>>
<<set $fuelLeft to 46.5>>
<<set $fuelRight to 46.5>>
The truck finishes the King Air at nine and rolls the twenty steps to the Seneca. The right side takes 20.1 gallons. You watch the meter do it and feel the number land somewhere between vindication and annoyance: Walt's "right at half" was off by four gallons in the unhelpful direction, and now it doesn't matter at all. The left side takes 0.4, a polite burp. Ninety-three aboard. You reset the JPI to 93 yourself, and initial the fuel log under Walt's note.

The receipt is $167 of criminal gas and one line of Manny's tidy handwriting. Wheels up at 9:05, thirty-one minutes shy of an hour late, cleared as filed, climbing through a night that has gone fully dark.

<<goto "Climb_Out">>

:: Ramp_AsIs [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Departed with the load as found"])>>
The logic assembles itself while you walk back out: 74 aboard against 58 burned, a gauge with a documented habit of lying low, and a note from the man who pumped the gas. And the Seneca can move fuel in flight. That's what the crossfeed is for. Once you're level and leaned, you'll run the right engine off the fat left tank for a while and square the whole thing up at altitude, which is a plan, and plans count.

You start both, get the ATIS, and call clearance with the cake secure and Elena's seat reclined one notch. Cleared to El Paso International as filed, ten thousand. Wheels up at 8:12 into the last usable dusk, the Hill Country going gray-blue under the left wing.

<<goto "Climb_Out">>

:: Ramp_Splash [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Quick splash in the right tank"])>>
<<set $splashed to true>>
Manny is fast and cheerful about it. The avgas truck grumbles over, and the meter starts spinning into the right wing. At 8.4 gallons the line shack radio calls his name twice, the Falcon crew already walking. "That's gotta be it, boss." He caps the tank, hands you the ticket to sign: 8.4 GAL 100LL. Close enough to the ten you asked for that neither of you says anything about it.

You bump the JPI to 82 to match and note the buy in the log under Walt's line. The gauge needle now sits solidly past half, which proves mostly that needles move when you feed them.

Wheels up at 8:25, cleared as filed, climbing west into a sky with one planet in it and not much else.

<<set $fuelRight to 34.9>>
<<goto "Climb_Out">>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Climb_Out [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Climbout and level at 10,000"])>>
The Seneca climbs the way the turbos always make it climb, steady and a little smug about it, thirty-one inches all the way up while the singles you learned in would have been gasping. San Antonio Departure hands you west. The Hill Country goes by underneath as a scatter of ranch lights getting stingier by the mile<<if $toppedOff>>, fully dark now, the last dusk long gone<<else>>, the horizon ahead losing its last deep blue<</if>>.

Level at ten thousand seventeen minutes after the wheels came up. You set 65%, lean both sides to the partnership numbers, and watch the EDM columns settle. Fuel flow left 10.4. Fuel flow right 11.3. The right side runs a hair thirsty at matched power, exactly like the squawk sheet says, for whichever reason the squawk sheet declines to specify.

Houston Center is quiet tonight, working three airplanes you can hear and probably six you can't. Elena tells the story of your father and the toast he tried to give, complete with impressions. Junction's little grid of lights slides under the nose at thirty-nine minutes.

<<if $toppedOff>><<goto "Cruise_D2_Topped">><<elseif $splashed>><<goto "Cruise_D2_Splash">><<else>><<goto "Cruise_D2_AsIs">><</if>>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_D2_AsIs [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Cruise: the reroute lands mid-plan"])>>
The fuel plan has a time on it. At the top of the hour, eight minutes from now, you'll run the right engine off the fat left tank for a while: right selector to X-FEED, boost pump on for the switch, let the heavy side carry both straws until the gauges agree with each other. You've walked through it once on the ground with Walt talking over your shoulder. Tonight will be the first time it matters.

Elena is halfway through the part where your father stood up with the wrong glass when Center keys up.

"November seven four six two Charlie, advise ready to copy amendment to routing."

You copy: cleared to El Paso International via direct Fort Stockton VORTAC, direct. Military airspace active south of the route tonight. You read it back, twist the heading bug a degree, and start rebuilding the flight plan in the GPS while Elena holds the story in the air, patient, one finger raised to mark her place.

The box takes the new routing. The frequency crackles about somebody else's altitude. Your eight minutes have become four, and the checklist flow you were mid-way through is somewhere behind you.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Interruption</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Run the cruise flow again from the first line. If a checklist got interrupted, it didn't happen." "Cruise_D2A_Restart">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: restarted the flow from the top"])>>
  <<set $d2 to "restart">><<set $fuelSeen to true>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You know where you left off. Finish listening to the story, then pick the flow back up at the fuel step." "Cruise_D2B_Memory">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: trusted memory for the flow"])>>
  <<set $d2 to "memory">><<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Spin the panel timer to fifteen minutes as a hard reminder for the fuel step, then let the cabin come back." "Cruise_D2C_Timer">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: set a timer for the fuel step"])>>
  <<set $d2 to "timer">><<set $fuelSeen to true>>
<</link>>

<<link "D. Ask Elena for a quiet cockpit for a few minutes while you rebuild the picture from scratch." "Cruise_D2D_Quiet">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: asked for a sterile cockpit"])>>
  <<set $d2 to "quiet">>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_D2A_Restart [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Flow restart interrupted again"])>>
"Hold that thought," you tell Elena, and she pinches the story between two fingers and holds it up like evidence.

Top of the flow. Power set, checked. Mixtures, checked. Cowl flaps trailed. Fuel panel: your eye crosses the gauges, left fat, right needle loafing under half the way it has all evening, and as your hand starts toward the selector the frequency opens up again.

"Six two Charlie, further amendment when ready, direct El Paso now approved, and traffic twelve o'clock, three five miles, opposite direction, a Baron at niner thousand."

Copy, readback, direct El Paso, traffic in sight a minute later as a strobe sliding down the right side. The checklist card has migrated under Elena's water bottle. When you pick the flow back up, it feels finished, the way a task feels finished when you've touched every part of it except one.

<<goto "Cruise_Enroute">>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_D2B_Memory [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Let the story finish first"])>>
Elena lands the story. It's a good one, and your father comes out of it better than he'd admit. She follows it with another about the cousins, and the night rolls under you at a hundred and thirty-seven across the ground, the box counting down miles to a VOR you no longer need.

The top of the hour arrives while you're laughing, and leaves while you're laughing, and does not send a card.

<<goto "Cruise_Enroute">>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_D2C_Timer [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Timer set, timer silenced"])>>
You spin the timer to fifteen minutes. As you do it your eye crosses the fuel panel: left fat, right needle loafing along under half, sticky gauge doing sticky gauge things. The plan has a backstop now. You let the cabin come back, and Elena finishes the story with both hands.

The timer goes off at 9:24 into a perfect little pileup. Center calls the handoff, "contact Albuquerque Center, one three five point eight seven five," the air gets a light chop off some invisible seam in the atmosphere, and Elena's water bottle rolls under your seat. You silence the beeper with a knuckle, mid-readback. Two minutes, you tell it.

Albuquerque checks you on. The chop smooths. The bottle is retrieved. The timer, which does not rearm itself, holds its peace all the way to the Davis Mountains.

<<goto "Cruise_Enroute">>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_D2D_Quiet [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Sterile cockpit rebuild"])>>
"Give me five quiet minutes," you say. "New routing, want to rebuild the picture."

"Say no more." Elena clicks on her book light and is instantly somewhere else. It's a good trick. You suspect the NICU taught it to her.

You rebuild: routing verified against the terrain ladder, Fort Stockton VOR tuned and identified out of pure habit, fuel totalizer glanced, 49 remaining, a few gallons under the plan line, which is about what the climb always costs. You brief yourself on the miss at El Paso like a good instrument pilot. By the time you wave Elena back in, the airplane feels squared away, every corner tucked.

The feeling of having done work is a convincing stand-in for the one piece of work you didn't do. The fuel selectors sit where they've sat since the runup, and nothing about a tidy cockpit says otherwise.

<<goto "Cruise_Enroute">>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_Enroute [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The long dark middle"])>>
<<if $d2 is "timer">>West of Ozona the last of the ground light gives out.<<else>>Somewhere abeam Ozona, Center hands you to Albuquerque, and the last of the ground light gives out.<</if>> The cirrus shield has slid over the top of the world like a lid. No moon behind it. No stars through it. The instrument glow, Elena's book light, and away off the left wingtip the thin beaded string of Interstate 10, trucks forty minutes apart.

<<if $waltTexted>>Your phone, riding in the door pocket, buzzes once against the airframe. Walt, from the dance hall: <em>"Gauge on the right sticks below half, its on the squawk sheet. More in it than it shows. Youre fine. Dance floor calling. W"</em> He types like he flies, no wasted motion. You put the phone back.

<</if>>The EDM does its patient arithmetic. Fuel flow left 10.4, right 11.3. Groundspeed 137 against the 145 you planned, the westerly running eight knots more honest than its forecast. <<if $fuelSeen>>Your eye keeps drifting back to the right fuel needle, which is somewhere in the neighborhood of a quarter, which is the neighborhood it lies about.<<else>>The fuel needles sit where fuel needles sit, and nothing on the panel raises its hand.<</if>> Elena has folded into the seat with her jacket for a pillow, breathing slow.

Two hours and five minutes out of San Antonio. Fort Stockton's little constellation came and went behind the left wing a while ago. Ahead there is nothing to see and a hundred and fifty miles of it.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "The miles grind west." "Fail_Onset">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Approaching the failure point"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Fail_Onset [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Right engine quits, windmilling"])>>
At two hours nine minutes, the right engine clears its throat.

A surge. A drop. A surge again, the airframe shivering with it. Then a smooth, powerless nothing. The nose slews right. The autopilot cranks the yoke left, holding heading with aileron like it was taught, and the airplane settles into a lazy sideways lean.

Sounds stack up. The left engine drones on alone at a new, naked pitch. Elena comes awake with a sharp breath. "What was that. What is that." Albuquerque is talking to a Southwest flight about ride reports. The right prop is a gray disk in the dark, windmilling, dragging.

The panel, all at once: right manifold pressure down at ambient. Right RPM sagging, prop still turning. Right EGT columns collapsing floor-ward. Right fuel flow needle on zero. Airspeed 122 and unwinding. Altitude ten thousand, starting to wander. The right fuel gauge lies flat on its empty peg, and the left one sits fat above half, and the totalizer glows a self-assured 22.7.

Outside there is one darkness, and it does not care which engine you believe in.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Right Engine</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Memory items, now, crisp, the way you drilled them: mixtures, props, throttles forward, identify, verify, feather. A windmilling prop is drag and risk at night." "SE_Secured">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D3: immediate memory items, feathered the right"])>>
  <<set $rightSecured to true>><<set $featherFast to true>><<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Airplane first. Autopilot off, rudder in, wings level, pitch for the blue side of 100, trim. Then figure out what just happened." "Fail_FlyFirst">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D3: flew the airplane first"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Your eyes and right hand go straight for the fuel panel. Flow, selectors, pumps. Engines quit for reasons, and the reasons live down there." "Fail_DiagRush">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D3: went straight for the fuel panel"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "D. Key the mic first. Albuquerque can see every airport in Texas, and you want them in the loop while you have ten thousand feet of options." "Fail_RadioFirst">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D3: called Center first"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Fail_FlyFirst [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Stabilized before troubleshooting"])>>
Autopilot off with a thumb. Right rudder... no. Left rudder, dead foot right, the lean straightens out. Wings level. You let the nose come down a degree and the airspeed stops unwinding at 104. Trim. Three breaths. The airplane is flying, descending a lazy hundred feet a minute on one engine's power at cruise altitude, and nothing about that is an emergency yet.

"Talk to me," Elena says, very level.

"Right engine quit. Airplane's fine. Give me a minute."

Now the survey, in the order you were taught to read a sick engine: right fuel flow, zero. It was zero before you touched anything. Right EGTs, cold and getting colder. Manifold pressure, ambient. Prop windmilling. That is not a broken engine's signature. Broken engines shake, spike, smoke, seize. This one just stopped eating.

The right fuel gauge is on the peg. The left is fat. The selectors sit where they've been since the runup: both ON, each engine drinking its own wing.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: Diagnose or Commit</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Feed it. Right boost pump on, right selector across the gate to X-FEED, and give the windmilling engine the left wing's fuel." "Restart_Crossfeed">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D4: crossfed the right engine, restart attempt"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Secure it by the book. Stable flight, then checklist: identify, verify, feather. You can sort out fuel theories with the drag cleaned up." "SE_Secured">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D4: secured and feathered the right"])>>
  <<set $rightSecured to true>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Tell Albuquerque what you have before you move a single lever. Altitude, options, and a second brain on frequency." "Fail_RadioSecond">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D4: radioed before touching the panel"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Fail_DiagRush [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Heads-down at the fuel panel"])>>
Your right hand finds the fuel panel and your head goes down with it. Right fuel flow zero. Right gauge on the peg. Selectors both ON. The story assembles itself fast and ugly: the right tank is dry, or near enough dry that the pickup is drinking air, and there is a fat left tank eight feet from a starving engine.

The airplane, unattended, does what airplanes do. The autopilot holds heading with crossed controls, speed bleeding, a slow sag off altitude. Somewhere in your scan the airspeed says 96. Then 91. The trim starts a low complaint you can feel through the floor.

"Hey." Elena's voice, tighter. "We're leaning."

Blue line is 89. You are two knots above it with your head in the pedestal.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Airplane or the Valve</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Airplane first, valve second. Push the nose over, kill the autopilot, wings level, speed back. The selector will still be there in ten seconds." "Restart_Crossfeed">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Recovered speed first, then crossfed"])>>
  <<set $speedScare to true>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You're one motion from fixing the actual problem. Boost pump on, selector across to X-FEED, then clean up the flying." "Restart_Crossfeed">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Finished the fuel panel heads-down"])>>
  <<set $headsDown to true>><<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Fail_RadioFirst [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Radioed Center at onset"])>>
"Albuquerque, Seneca seven four six two Charlie, we've lost power on the right engine, ten thousand, troubleshooting."

The reply comes back in the flat, instant calm they save for exactly this. "Seneca seven four six two Charlie, roger. Say souls and fuel remaining."

"Two souls, about an hour of fuel, six two Charlie." The totalizer's number, out of your mouth before you've examined it.

"Six two Charlie, roger. Nearest airports: Fort Stockton, four six miles southeast of your position, field elevation three thousand eleven. Pecos, two four northeast, be advised Pecos weather reporting is out of service. El Paso, one three eight west. Say intentions."

Twenty-five seconds gone. The airplane has spent them drifting: speed 101, a wing that wants to drop, two hundred feet off the altitude. The right prop windmills. The right fuel flow needle, you now notice, is sitting on zero like it's been there a while.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: Intentions</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. 'Stand by, six two Charlie.' Stabilize, then run the fuel panel: boost on, right selector to X-FEED, feed the engine from the left wing." "Restart_Crossfeed">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Stabilized, then crossfed the right"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. 'Six two Charlie will secure the engine and advise.' Identify, verify, feather, and take the drag out of the night." "SE_Secured">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Told Center, then feathered"])>>
  <<set $rightSecured to true>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Fail_RadioSecond [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Briefed Center from stable flight"])>>
"Albuquerque, Seneca seven four six two Charlie, right engine quit at ten thousand, windmilling, airplane's stable, troubleshooting. Two souls."

"Six two Charlie, roger. Nearest airports: Fort Stockton four six southeast, Pecos two four northeast with weather reporting out of service, El Paso one three eight on the nose. Advise intentions when able."

Clean, useful, and thirty seconds spent. The airplane holds 102 where you trimmed it, bleeding a patient hundred feet a minute. The right fuel flow needle hasn't moved off zero. The left tank sits fat. The selectors sit at ON.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Lever or the Detent</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Right boost pump on, right selector to X-FEED. If it's starvation, the engine tells you inside ten seconds." "Restart_Crossfeed">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Crossfed after the radio call"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Feather it and fly the single-engine profile. A relight experiment can wait until you're pointed at a runway." "SE_Secured">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Feathered after the radio call"])>>
  <<set $rightSecured to true>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Restart_Crossfeed [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The right engine relights on crossfeed"])>>
<<set $restored to true>><<set $crossfeedState to "rightFromLeft">>
<<if $speedScare>>Nose down, autopilot off, wings level. The speed comes back up through 95 and the trim stops complaining. Then, deliberately, one item at a time:<<elseif $headsDown>>Your hand does it in one motion while the airspeed grinds down through 84, the yoke going mushy, Elena's hand braced flat on the glareshield:<<else>>Deliberately, one item at a time, the way the POH lays it out:<</if>> right boost pump ON. Right selector out of its spring gate, across, into X-FEED. Mixture rich.

One second. Two. Three, and the fuel flow needle lifts off its peg like nothing was ever wrong.

The right engine inhales, fires on four cylinders, then six, surges once against the governor, and settles into sync so smoothly it feels like an apology. EGTs climb their little ladders. Manifold pressure comes home. You walk the throttle up gently, minding the turbo, and the Seneca is a twin again.

<<if $headsDown>>You level the wings and pull the nose up through the recovery, 84 knots and nine thousand five hundred where there used to be ten thousand, heart doing a drum solo.<<else>>Total time from quit to running: under two minutes. Altitude spent: a few hundred feet.<</if>> The right engine is running on the left wing's fuel through the crossfeed. The right tank is a 46.5 gallon bottle of air.

Elena exhales slowly. "Okay," she says. "Okay. That sounded expensive."

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "Now the arithmetic." "Cruise_D4_Restored">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Taking stock after the relight"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_D4_Restored [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The restored-engine decision"])>>
Both engines run. Both of them are drinking from the left tank, through one selector sitting in a detent labeled X-FEED. Everything you have left is on one side of the airplane, and the totalizer says that everything is 22 gallons. The EDM's combined flow reads 21.7 an hour. You can do that division without a pencil: an hour, give or take the descent.

The map does the rest. El Paso, 138 miles ahead into the wind, an hour and a minute of flying plus the arrival. Fort Stockton, 46 miles behind the left shoulder with the wind helping, twenty-some minutes, a 7,500 foot runway, an ASOS, and a self-serve pump you have actually used in daylight. Pecos, 24 miles off the right rear, no weather source tonight and its long runway NOTAMed closed. You cross Pecos off and the map gets simpler.

Elena has her hand loose on the cake box strap. "Do whatever you need to do," she says. "I trust you. You know that." She checks her phone without meaning to. The lock screen says 10:24, and her alarm lives five hours and fifty minutes away.

Albuquerque, softly: "Six two Charlie, say status when able."

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: Restored</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Turn around. Fort Stockton, fuel in both wings, and El Paso an hour late with the math boring again." "Divert_FST_Turn">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D5: turned back to Fort Stockton for fuel"])>>
  <<set $divert to "KFST">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Continue to El Paso and say the words: minimum fuel. An hour of fuel for an hour of flying, with the whole system watching your sequence." "Cruise_KELP_Advise">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D5: continued to KELP, advised minimum fuel"])>>
  <<set $declared to "min">>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Continue to El Paso, status normal. The problem was distribution, you found it, you fixed it, and the totalizer math still closes." "Cruise_KELP_Quiet">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D5: continued to KELP, told no one"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_KELP_Advise [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Minimum fuel westbound"])>>
"Albuquerque, Seneca seven four six two Charlie. Right engine ran a tank dry, we've restored it on crossfeed. Continuing El Paso, and be advised, six two Charlie is minimum fuel."

"Six two Charlie, roger, minimum fuel. No delay expected on your routing. El Paso altimeter three zero zero five. Advise if your situation upgrades."

<em>Upgrades.</em> Controllers pick their verbs carefully. What you've told the system is: no reserve for surprises, keep the surprises away from me. What you have not told them is that you need the priority of an emergency, because you don't, quite, yet.

The Seneca drones west with both engines sipping from the left wing. You watch the totalizer walk down through 20, through 18, the right gauge dead on its peg, the left gauge starting its own long slide. Elena is quiet in the way of someone doing math they don't like. The lights of El Paso are somewhere behind the curve of the dark.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Fuel Panel</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Leave the panel exactly as it is, right selector in X-FEED, until the airplane is parked. It's ugly, and it's feeding both engines." "Approach_ELP_Min">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Left the crossfeed alone to landing"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Normalize it for the arrival. The landing checklist says selectors ON, and a stable descent is the right time to put the panel back to standard." "Fail_Restumble">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Moved the right selector back to ON"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Fail_Restumble [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The right engine quits a second time"])>>
<<set $restumble to true>><<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
You reach down and put the right selector back where the placard likes it. ON. The engine keeps running on the fuel already in its lines, which is a sentence with a clock in it.

Forty seconds later the right fuel flow sags. Then the surge, the cough, the yaw, the whole rotten song from an hour ago, and this time you know every note of it. Selector back across to X-FEED. Boost pump. Three seconds that bill by the heartbeat, and the engine inhales and comes back to work.

"What <em>was</em> that," Elena says, both hands flat on her thighs.

"Me," you say, which is the truest thing said on this airplane all night. The placard says ON because ON assumes fuel. The right wing has no fuel. Normal is not a switch position tonight. Normal is wherever the gasoline is.

<<goto "Approach_ELP_Min">>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Approach_ELP_Min [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Arrival at El Paso, priority handling"])>>
<<if $seq is "confessed">>The frequency changes temperature immediately. "Six two Charlie, understood, cancel the sequence. Fly heading two six five, direct when able, runway two six left, you're number one. Say fuel in minutes." Minutes. You give them fifteen and hope you're sandbagging.<<else>>Approach takes the handoff with your minimum fuel already on the strip. "Seneca six two Charlie, El Paso Approach, no delay tonight, expect the visual two six left, the RNAV Yankee two six left is available if you want the needles." You want the needles. On a black night with one wet wing, you brief it and load it.<</if>>

The descent is the longest arithmetic problem of your life. Totalizer 8.9 starting down<<if $restumble>>, a little less than it would have been before your experiment with the placard<</if>>. The city comes up over the curve all at once, a bowl of amber light with the Franklins a black island in the middle of it. The left gauge is in the last eighth, where every error the gauge ever had lives rent-free.

Tower, 118.3: "Seneca six two Charlie, wind variable at three, runway two six left, cleared to land. Trucks are standing by, courtesy of Approach."

Nine thousand feet of runway you could land across, not just on. The flare happens somewhere over the numbers, the chirp, the rollout, and both engines keep running the whole way to the high-speed, which by the totalizer's opinion was not guaranteed.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "Shut down on the FBO ramp and let the night catch up to you." "End_ELP_MinFuel">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed KELP, minimum fuel"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_KELP_Quiet [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continuing quiet to El Paso"])>>
"Albuquerque, six two Charlie, we're back to normal ops, continuing El Paso."

"Six two Charlie, roger."

And that's it. The system files you under fine. The frequency moves on to a Lajitas-bound Caravan and somebody's ride report, and nobody between here and the Rio Grande knows that everything keeping this airplane in the air is sloshing in one wing with an hour on the meter.

It was distribution, not quantity. You found it, you fixed it, the engine has run flawlessly since the relight. Declaring things costs conversations, paperwork, maybe a call from a number you don't recognize. The totalizer says the math closes: 22 aboard at the relight, an hour and change of flying. It closes. It just doesn't close with anything left over.

Elena watches the black nothing go by for a while. "How's the gas," she asks, casual as a heart monitor.

"We're fine."

The word sits in the cockpit like a third passenger. West of the Guadalupe shadow the city glow finally lifts over the horizon, and the totalizer walks down through 9 as you start downhill.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "Descend into the El Paso arrival and take what the night hands you." "Approach_ELP_Seq">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Started down into the sequence"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Approach_ELP_Seq [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Sequenced behind the airline traffic"])>>
Approach is friendly and busy. "Seneca six two Charlie, El Paso Approach, information X-ray current. Fly heading two four zero, vector for sequencing, you're number two following a Boeing seven thirty-seven, ten o'clock, one two miles, runway two six left. Caution wake turbulence."

Number two. The heading takes you south of the field, away from the runway, standard as a Tuesday morning, five extra minutes for spacing behind ninety tons of company traffic. The totalizer says 5.8. The left gauge needle lies against the last hash mark and quivers with the engines. Elena has found the grab handle without looking like she was looking for it.

The system is treating you like a normal airplane, because you told it you were one.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: Number Two</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Take the vector and fly the sequence. Five minutes of spacing is what the math has left in it, and asking now means explaining the last hour." "End_ELP_Fumes">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Accepted the sequence"])>>
  <<set $seq to "accepted">><<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Say it now, late but out loud: an engine ran a tank dry tonight, everything aboard is in one wing, and six two Charlie needs the runway, not the sequence." "Approach_ELP_Min">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Confessed late, asked for priority"])>>
  <<set $seq to "confessed">><<set $declared to "late">>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Divert_FST_Turn [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Turned back for Fort Stockton"])>>
"Albuquerque, Seneca seven four six two Charlie. Right engine ran its tank dry, we've restored it on crossfeed. We're going to turn around and take fuel at Fort Stockton."

"Six two Charlie, roger, cleared direct Fort Stockton, maintain ten thousand, descend at your discretion. Fort Stockton ASOS one one eight point five two five, traffic none observed. Nice quiet night for it."

The turn feels like the wrong direction the whole way around the compass rose, El Paso's promise sliding off the nose, the tailwind picking you up like a conveyor. A hundred and seventy-eight across the ground going east. Twenty minutes to pavement.

"We're going back?" Elena asks, and then hears it. "Backwards but with gas. Okay." She thinks. "I'll text Dee from the ground. Worst case she preps my first kiddo." She looks at the black where the window should be. "You'd rather owe an apology than an explanation. Dad says that."

Dad got it from a flight instructor, but tonight is not the night to fight over the estate.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "Set up the descent into a dark airport." "Approach_FST_R">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Descending eastbound for KFST"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Approach_FST_R [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Black-hole arrival, Fort Stockton"])>>
The ASOS reads itself to you in its flat robot Texan: wind one six zero at six, visibility one zero, sky clear below one two thousand, altimeter three zero zero four. Runway 12 it is, mostly aligned, light on the nose.

Fort Stockton's beacon shows up first, a lonely white-green metronome, then the town beyond it. You cancel IFR with Albuquerque, who tells you to have a good night in a voice that means it, and you key the mic seven times on 122.8. The runway lights step up out of the dark, two amber rails laid on nothing, MIRL coming off preset-low like the field waking up for you. The PAPI was burning already. Two white, two red, faithful as a dog.

You fly the PAPI like it's carved in stone, because between the last ranch light and the threshold there is no horizon, no texture, no anything, just the black-hole approach every night-flying article warns about, at an airport where the nearest human is asleep two miles away. Crossfeed still feeding the right engine. Boost pumps on. Final at 95, over the lights, chirp, rollout long and lazy on 7,500 feet of asphalt.

You roll to the end, swing around, announce the backtaxi to nobody, and follow your own landing light up the runway to the ramp, where one sodium lamp holds a little dome of orange over the self-serve island.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "Shut down at the pumps." "Ground_FST_Pump">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Shutdown at the self-serve island"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Ground_FST_Pump [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The self-serve saga"])>>
The props tick down to silence, and the silence out here has a size to it. Gyros winding down. The cooling engines pinging. Somewhere a very long way off, a truck on I-10 changing gears.

Elena climbs down onto the ramp, hugs her elbows, and stands looking at the airplane for a while without saying anything at all. The quiet has a size to it too.

The pump island takes its tribute in order. The partnership debit card declines. It declines again, with feeling, because the card has a nightly limit nobody remembered. Your personal card works. The static cable reel fights you, the ladder is bolted a foot too far from where any Seneca wing has ever been, and the hose weighs what hoses weigh. You put twenty-five a side in, watching the meter's slow wheel, and for the first time tonight both fuel gauges tell the same story.

$332 on the receipt. The pump's printer sounds like it's clearing its throat of ten years of dust.

"Okay," Elena says finally, quietly, from the edge of the light. "That, back there. How bad was that, actually? Scale of one to the things you don't tell Mom."

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "Tell her straight, then decide what the rest of the night looks like." "Ground_FST_D6">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The honest ramp conversation"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Ground_FST_D6 [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Go tonight or stay"])>>
You tell her straight: the tank ran dry because the fuel was loaded crooked and you flew the total instead of the sides. The engine was never broken. The fix took ten seconds. The scary part wasn't the engine, it was how reasonable every step to it felt.

She nods slowly. "Okay." A small laugh with no humor in it. "You're the only person I know who'd fail an exam and then grade it harder than the professor."

Your phone rings. Walt. The group text you sent from the ramp has reached the dance hall. "The note said half," he opens, defensive as a man on one foot. "Gauge said half. I never top the right side, the vent weeps, it's on the list." A pause you don't fill. "I figured you'd fuel to your own numbers anyway. I would've." That one lands, because he's right, and you both know it, and neither of you says so. He offers to cover the gas. You tell him you'll sort the log Monday, all three partners, in person. Priya, from a radiology conference in Denver, contributes three question marks.

It is 11:05. El Paso is fifty-two minutes of flying away, both tanks honest. The Sandstone Inn by the interstate has a room and a 5 a.m. lobby coffee. Elena's alarm goes off at 5:15 either way.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: Where Tonight Ends</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Fly it home. You're rested enough, the airplane is fixed and fat with fuel, and Elena wakes up in her own bed with her shift intact." "End_FST_GoAgain">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D6: flew home the same night"])>>
  <<set $ground to "go">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Call it. Two hours of adrenaline is its own fatigue, and the Sandstone Inn beats discovering the night's third surprise at altitude." "End_FST_Overnight">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D6: stayed the night in Fort Stockton"])>>
  <<set $ground to "stay">>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_D2_Splash [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Cruise on the splash, rerouted"])>>
The splash sits in your mental ledger as a solved problem: the note said half, the order said ten, and even the sticky gauge came up past the halfway hash before you taxied. No juggling required tonight. Just fly.

Elena is deep into the story of your father and the wrong glass when Houston Center calls with an amendment: cleared to El Paso International via direct Fort Stockton VORTAC, direct, military airspace active south of the route. You copy it on your leg, read it back, and rebuild the box while she holds the story mid-air with one finger raised.

The new magenta line settles. The frequency moves on. The evening reassembles itself around the interruption the way evenings do, mostly.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: After the Amendment</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Run the whole problem again from the top: time, fuel, and burn against the new clearance, before the story resumes." "Cruise_JPI">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: re-ran the numbers after the reroute"])>>
  <<set $d2 to "smath">><<set $fuelSeen to true>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. The box has the route and the fuel was solved on the ground. Verify the terrain ladder, then let Elena land the story." "Cruise_JPI">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: verified terrain, resumed the evening"])>>
  <<set $d2 to "sflow">>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Ask for a few quiet minutes and rebuild the entire picture, new route, new brief, before anything else happens." "Cruise_JPI">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: quiet cockpit rebuild after reroute"])>>
  <<set $d2 to "squiet">>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_JPI [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The fuel-flow discrepancy at Ozona"])>>
An hour and forty minutes out, the world has narrowed to the panel glow and one string of interstate lights crawling along off the left wing. Fort Stockton's beacon is just picking itself out of the black, twenty-three miles off the nose. Albuquerque Center has you now.

The EDM has been keeping a quiet ledger all evening, and somewhere over Ozona it becomes impossible not to audit. Right fuel flow: 11.4. Left: 10.4. The plan said ten a side. The squawk sheet says the right side reads high, unclear whether it's the transducer talking or the injectors, service scheduled for April. The right fuel gauge has sagged below three-eighths, which is either the truth or the sticky sender's favorite lie. The totalizer says 41.5 aboard, comfortably on plan, splendidly indifferent to which wing.

<<if $waltTexted>>Your phone buzzes against the door pocket. Walt: <em>"Gauge on the right sticks below half, its on the squawk sheet. More in it than it shows. Youre fine. Dance floor calling. W"</em>

<</if>>Three instruments, a squawk sheet, and a note<<if $waltTexted>>, now with a text message concurring from a dance hall in Fabens<</if>>. If the 11.4 is real burn, the right tank's arithmetic gets thin somewhere around the descent. If it's indication error, everything is fine and it always was. Nothing on the panel volunteers which.

Elena, half asleep: "Why'd the engine sound change?" It didn't. You leaned forward, and the seat creaked, and she noticed. Nurses.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Number That Doesn't Match</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Believe the ugliest number. If the right side truly burns 11.4, it runs out before the flare, and the lit, sleeping airport twenty miles ahead sells gas. Land at Fort Stockton and know." "Divert_FSTP_Arr">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D3: believed the worst case, landing FST"])>>
  <<set $divert to "KFST-precautionary">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Watch it. The spread is inside instrument slop, the splash covered the note's gap with gallons to spare, and the totalizer sits dead on plan. Continue, eyes on the right side." "Cruise_West_Splash">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D3: filed it as gauge slop, continued"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Split the difference with the system you own: right engine to X-FEED for a while, rest the suspect tank on the fat one, and switch back for the descent." "Cruise_West_Managed">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D3: crossfed as insurance"])>>
  <<set $crossfeedState to "insurance">>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Divert_FSTP_Arr [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Precautionary stop, Fort Stockton"])>>
"Albuquerque, Seneca seven four six two Charlie, we'd like to make a precautionary fuel stop at Fort Stockton, request lower."

"Six two Charlie, roger, cleared direct Fort Stockton, descend at your discretion, ASOS one one eight point five two five. Advise cancellation on the ground or in the air."

Both engines run perfectly all the way down, which does nothing at all for your certainty and everything for your options. ASOS calls it wind one six zero at six. You cross over the field at pattern altitude plus a thousand, pick out the runway 12 rails after seven clicks on 122.8 wake the MIRL up, and swing around a left downwind with the PAPI keeping honest score. The landing is the unremarkable kind that never makes anyone's logbook remarks column.

You taxi to the island of sodium light at the pumps and shut down into that enormous West Texas quiet. Elena stretches. "Pit stop?"

"Pit stop. Ten years from now this is either the smartest twenty minutes I ever spent or a story Walt tells at Christmas."

"Can't it be both?"

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "Put the meter on the question." "Ground_FSTP">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Fueling at the self-serve, precautionary"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Ground_FSTP [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The meter settles the argument"])>>
The card reader spits out the partnership debit twice before your personal card buys forgiveness. You drag the hose up the ladder and fill the right side first, watching the meter's little wheels, because the meter is the only instrument on this airport with no opinions.

The right tank takes 34.7 gallons.

Which means it held 11.8 when the wheels touched. Which means the 11.4 fuel flow was real burn, not indication, and the arithmetic you ran at Ozona was the correct one: another hour of "watching it" and the right engine would have gone quiet somewhere in the descent over the darkest dirt in Texas. You stand on the ladder in the sodium light doing the subtraction twice more, because it keeps producing the same number, and the number keeps being worth staring at.

You top the left with 26.3 and cap it. Both gauges, for the first time tonight, agree with a meter.

Elena watches your face. "That's your serious math face. How close was it?"

"Closer than the note said. Not as close as it could've gotten."

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Fuel Log</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Call Walt right now, dance hall or not. The note said half, the meter says otherwise, and the conversation shouldn't age until Monday." "End_FST_Prudent">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Called Walt from the ramp"])>>
  <<set $waltPlan to "call">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Text the partnership thread the meter numbers, no commentary, and have the conversation Monday with everyone's blood pressure at rest." "End_FST_Prudent">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Texted the meter numbers to the thread"])>>
  <<set $waltPlan to "text">>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Write it in the log the way the log deserves: gallons, by the meter, both sides, dated. Let the numbers make the argument at annual." "End_FST_Prudent">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Logged the numbers, saved the words"])>>
  <<set $waltPlan to "log">>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_West_Splash [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Watching the right side westbound"])>>
The right fuel flow holds 11.4 like it's proud of it. The gauge keeps sagging, a needle-width at a time, through territory where the sticky sender has cried wolf before. The totalizer stays serene. Fort Stockton's beacon slides down the left side and gets swallowed by the black, and after it there is nothing out the windshield but the panel's reflection until the earth's curve finally coughs up a smudge of El Paso glow, fifty minutes of nothing later.

Top of descent comes at two hours thirty-six. Approach clears you down and gives you the numbers: information X-ray, wind variable at three, runway two six left. Elena reorganizes herself upright and starts putting her shoes on, one hand braced on the cake box.

Descending through seventy-four hundred, twenty-one miles east of the field, the right engine surges.

Then the cough. The fuel flow needle falls over. The EGTs start their cold slide, the prop windmills, and the Seneca leans right and pulls against the trim, low over the dark shelf of desert east of the mountains with the city lights spread out ahead like an unkept promise. The right gauge lies on its peg. The left sits at a quarter and a bit. Approach is talking to a Southwest flight about a gate.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: Low, Dark, and Close</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Fuel starvation, caught in the act: right boost pump on, right selector across to X-FEED, and give it three seconds to come back." "Approach_ELP_Relight">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D4: crossfed and relit on the arrival"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. No experiments at thirty-four hundred AGL at night: identify, verify, feather, declare, and fly the single-engine arrival you've trained for." "Approach_ELP_ArrOEI">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D4: feathered on the arrival"])>>
  <<set $rightSecured to true>><<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Airport first: tell Approach you've lost an engine and want the runway, then work the problem with the path cleared." "Fail_ArrRadio">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D4: called Approach before troubleshooting"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Fail_ArrRadio [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Told Approach first, arrival failure"])>>
<<set $seq to "arrTold">>
"El Paso Approach, Seneca seven four six two Charlie, we've lost power on the right engine, descending through seven thousand, two souls."

The frequency snaps to attention. "Six two Charlie, roger, fly heading two six five, direct the field when able, runway two six left, cleared to land when you get there, equipment will be standing by. Say fuel remaining."

Fifteen seconds, and the path to the airport now belongs to you. The airplane has spent those seconds sagging through sixty-eight hundred with the dead engine dragging, and the panel sits exactly where it sat: right fuel flow zero, right gauge on the peg, left tank holding what the left tank holds, selectors ON.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: With the Path Cleared</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Now the fuel panel: right boost on, right selector to X-FEED, three seconds of faith in the diagnosis." "Approach_ELP_Relight">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Crossfed after clearing the path"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Now the drill: feather the right, secure it, and take the single-engine arrival with the trucks already rolling." "Approach_ELP_ArrOEI">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Feathered after clearing the path"])>>
  <<set $rightSecured to true>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Approach_ELP_Relight [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Arrival relight on crossfeed"])>>
<<set $restored to true>><<set $crossfeedState to "rightFromLeft">>
Boost pump. Selector across the gate to X-FEED. One second, two, three, and the right engine drinks, fires, and hauls itself back into sync with a surge you feel in the rudder pedals. The whole event, from cough to cured, fits inside ninety seconds and one descending mile.

<<if $seq isnot "arrTold">>"Approach, Seneca seven four six two Charlie, we had a fuel starvation event on the right engine, it's restored on crossfeed, requesting straight-in two six left and we'd like the equipment to stand by anyway."

"Six two Charlie, straight-in two six left approved, cleared to land, equipment will be standing by."<<else>>"Approach, six two Charlie, engine's restored, it was fuel starvation, we're back on two engines, continuing straight-in."

"Six two Charlie, roger, cleared to land two six left, equipment's standing by regardless."<</if>>

The rest is fifteen of the most attentive miles of your life. Both engines drink from the left wing. The city rises up around the descent, runway lights blooming out of the amber sprawl, and the mains touch on 26L with the trucks idling along the parallel like patient chaperones.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "Roll out, thank everyone, and taxi in with your heart still doing arrivals." "End_ELP_Relight">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed 26L after the arrival relight"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Approach_ELP_ArrOEI [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Single-engine arrival into El Paso"])>>
Identify: dead foot right. Verify: right throttle, nothing. Feather: the lever back through the detent while the prop still windmills fast enough for the pins to allow it, and the blades knife to a stop against the city glow. Mixture cut, boost off, selector off, and the Seneca steadies into its one-engine lean.

"El Paso Approach, Seneca seven four six two Charlie declaring an emergency, right engine secured and feathered, two souls, three five minutes fuel, landing two six left."

"Six two Charlie, roger, cleared to land runway two six left, wind variable at three, equipment standing by. Anything you need, say the word."

You fly it like the sim session you never quite believed would come due: blue radial, gear when the runway is guaranteed, flaps in two thoughtful installments, a brief to Elena in plain words. The 9,025 feet of runway 26L absorbs the arrival without comment, trucks pacing the rollout, their light bars painting the cowlings red and white.

The feathered engine, a mechanic will confirm tomorrow, is in perfect health. It was just thirsty, eleven point four gallons an hour thirsty, exactly like the little gauge said.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "Shut down on the ramp and let the trucks go home." "End_ELP_ArrOEI">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed 26L single-engine"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_West_Managed [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Insurance crossfeed westbound"])>>
Right boost pump on. Right selector across to X-FEED. The right engine takes its next drink from the left wing without a flicker, and the suspect tank goes into escrow, its gallons frozen wherever the truth of them lies. You'll switch back at the top of descent, run the arrival on standard plumbing, and let the shop settle the injector question in April.

You brief the hook out loud, because it is one: "Right selector back to ON at top of descent." Elena, without opening her eyes: "Want me to remember something? I remember things for twelve hours at a stretch professionally."

"Right selector, top of descent."

"Right selector, top of descent," she repeats, in her taking-report voice, and sleeps.

The Guadalupes pass invisibly north. El Paso's glow lifts over the curve at two hours twenty, and Approach starts you downhill at two thirty-six with information X-ray and the visual to 26L on offer.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Hook</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Top of descent, so: descent flow now, deliberately, starting with the fuel panel. Right selector back to ON, boost through the switch, then the rest." "End_ELP_Managed">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ran the descent flow, caught the hook"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Approach is already issuing the arrival, so brief and fly first. The flow can run at the bottom of the descent where the workload lives anyway." "Approach_ELP_MgdLate">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Deferred the flow into the arrival"])>>
  <<set $mgdSwitch to true>><<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Approach_ELP_MgdLate [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The hook nearly forgotten"])>>
The arrival eats the descent exactly the way arrivals do: a crossing restriction, a traffic call, information X-ray refreshing to Yankee mid-brief, Elena waking up and finding her shoes. The flow waits politely at the bottom of the pile.

It surfaces on five-mile final, at the G of your GUMPS check. Gas. Your eye drops to the pedestal and finds the right selector still sitting in X-FEED, drinking the left wing, right where you parked it an hour ago over the Delaware Basin.

"Right selector," Elena says suddenly, bolt upright. "Top of descent. I owed you that at the top."

Selector to ON, boost pump covering the switch, and the right engine transitions tanks without so much as a hiccup, because tonight, unlike every other configuration of this evening, the tank it just got pointed at actually has fuel in it. Gear down and confirmed. Flaps. The landing is entirely ordinary and does not deserve to be.

<<goto "End_ELP_Managed">>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_D2_Topped [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Cruise with full tanks, rerouted"])>>
Ninety-three gallons ride behind you in two agreeing wings, and the flight has the settled feel of a problem paid off in cash. The only deficit is time: the clock says you'll be putting Elena's bag on her porch about eleven forty, Mountain, and her alarm does not negotiate.

She's mid-story about your father and the wrong glass when Houston Center calls the amendment: cleared to El Paso International via direct Fort Stockton VORTAC, direct, military airspace active south of the route. You copy, read back, and rebuild the box while she holds her place with one raised finger and impressive patience for someone running on cake and hotel coffee.

The magenta line redraws itself a few degrees north. The night out there stays the same color of nothing.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The New Line</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Walk the new routing against the terrain ladder and your minimum altitudes before the story resumes. New line, new look, every time." "Cruise_JPI_T">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: re-verified terrain on the new line"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. It's a two-degree dogleg over the same dirt. The box has it, Center owns the airspace, and Elena's story has a good part coming." "Cruise_JPI_T">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: accepted the dogleg, resumed the story"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Quiet cockpit for five minutes: rebuild the route, the ladder, and the descent plan from a clean sheet, then reopen the cabin." "Cruise_JPI_T">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: sterile rebuild on the new line"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_JPI_T [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Elena spots the split columns"])>>
Somewhere past the Fort Stockton beacon, deep in the black-bag half of Texas, Elena leans over and studies the engine monitor like a chart at the foot of a bed.

"Should those two match?" She taps the glass over the fuel flow columns. Left 10.4, right 11.3. "They've been different all night. I checked when we got in, I check things, it's a whole personality."

She's right, and it's the squawk sheet's line one wearing numbers: right side reads high, indication or actual, injector service in April. With ninety-three gallons aboard it's a curiosity instead of a countdown. It is also, some quiet part of you notes, the exact discrepancy you'd need to understand cold if the tanks were ever less friendly than tonight.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Columns</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Explain it to her properly, then log the observed split with the date and power setting for Walt and the shop. Data beats adjectives." "Approach_ELP_T">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D3: explained and logged the FF split"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Chase the number: lean the right side until the columns agree. Matched flows are tidy, and tidy is professional." "Approach_ELP_T">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D3: leaned the right side to match"])>>
  <<set $leanChase to true>><<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. 'Gauges do that.' It's squawked, it's scheduled, and tonight it's academic. Back to the story." "Approach_ELP_T">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D3: waved at the split"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Approach_ELP_T [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The black-bowl arrival"])>>
<<if $leanChase>>The right side runs leaner and warmer for a while, its EGTs riding higher up their bars than you like, until twenty minutes on a hunch you push the mixture back where the engine wanted it and the columns go back to disagreeing in peace.

<</if>>El Paso announces itself the way it always does from the east: nothing, nothing, nothing, then a whole civilization's worth of amber poured into a bowl between dark mountain shapes. Approach starts you down over the last of the empty, where the ground is a rumor under a cirrus lid, and offers the night's last decision: "Seneca six two Charlie, the visual runway two six left, or I can set you up for the RNAV Yankee two six left, your call."

The field sits at the bottom of the glow with the Franklins standing black behind it. Between you and the runway lie thirty miles of unlit shelf where the only depth cue is faith.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Last Thirty Miles</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Take the visual straight-in and fly it on raw eyes and the big picture. It's severe clear, and the runway is right there in the bowl." "End_TopOff_Home">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D4: visual straight-in, eyes only"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Take the visual, but load the RNAV Yankee two six left behind it and keep the glidepath needle honest all the way down the black." "End_TopOff_Home">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D4: visual with the RNAV backstop"])>>
  <<set $backstop to true>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: End_TopOff_Home [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: home with boring gauges"])>>
<<if $backstop>>The needle rides centered down the invisible slope while your eyes fly the lights, each instrument auditing the other, and the black shelf east of the field passes underneath as a solved problem instead of an act of faith.<<else>>You fly it on eyes and experience, and the runway grows in the windshield the way runways do over black ground: slowly, then suspiciously, then all at once. The radar altimeter in your inner ear files one complaint over the dark shelf that your landing light eventually overrules.<</if>> The mains touch 26L at ten past midnight, Central, which the time zone forgives into ten past eleven.

Elena is through her door at 11:40 Mountain. "Fifty-five minutes late," she says, hugging you. "I'll bill you." Then, over her shoulder, "Thank you for the gas. I counted. You made the guy put in every drop."

Sunday afternoon, after her shift, the partnership group chat acquires a photo of the $167 receipt from Mission Trail Aviation, captioned by Walt: <em>"$8.15!! criminal."</em> And a minute later, from Priya: <em>"Cheapest thing anyone bought this weekend."</em> Walt does not reply, which in Walt means yes.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>You looked at a fuel load that was legal by the totals and crooked by the sides, and you bought the boring answer: both tanks full, fifty-five minutes surrendered to the truck queue. The rest of the night was what full tanks make it. The reroute was an errand instead of a threat, the fuel-flow split was a logbook entry instead of a countdown, and the one real hazard left standing was the black-hole arrival<<if $backstop>>, which you handled with a needle backing up your eyes<<else>>, which you flew on eyes alone and got away with cleanly<</if>>.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>The ramp decision is the whole exam. The pressures against topping off were real and humanly sized: a promise to someone you love, a partner's grumbling about gas prices, a gauge with a documented habit of lying low, and a note from the guy who fueled it. Post-flight arithmetic settled what the estimates couldn't: the truck put 20.1 gallons in a tank the note called half-full and the gauge called three-eighths. Three estimates, zero measurements, until the meter voted. <<if $leanChase>>The one wobble was chasing the fuel-flow split with the mixture at night, treating a data question as a knob question. The engine answered by running hot until you put it back.<</if>> <<if $badchoices gte 2>>The reroute beat also cost you a terrain re-check that full tanks let you get away with skipping. Different night, different tanks, that habit bills differently.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Twins run on per-side arithmetic, and the only unimpeachable fuel instrument at a ramp is the meter on the truck. When estimates disagree, buying certainty is almost always cheapest, and 91.103's "all available information" quietly includes information you have to purchase. On the arrival: over unlit terrain at night, a loaded approach behind a visual costs thirty seconds of button pushing and removes the one illusion, the black-hole approach, that kills proficient pilots in clear air.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>Margin usually looks like a boring receipt and an hour you'll never get back. That's what it's supposed to look like.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readFlightPlan to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readMap to false>><<set $fuelLeft to 46.5>><<set $fuelRight to 26.5>><<set $toppedOff to false>><<set $splashed to false>><<set $waltTexted to false>><<set $d2 to "">><<set $fuelSeen to false>><<set $rightSecured to false>><<set $featherFast to false>><<set $restored to false>><<set $airstart to false>><<set $declared to "none">><<set $crossfeedState to "normal">><<set $inversion to false>><<set $speedScare to false>><<set $headsDown to false>><<set $restumble to false>><<set $doubleScare to false>><<set $divert to "">><<set $seq to "">><<set $waltPlan to "">><<set $ground to "">><<set $backstop to false>><<set $leanChase to false>><<set $mgdSwitch to false>><<set $stab to "">><</link>>
</div>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: End_FST_Prudent [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: the precautionary fuel stop"])>>
<<if $waltPlan is "call">>Walt answers on the fifth ring with dance-hall behind him, listens to the meter numbers, and goes quiet long enough that you check the connection. "Thirty-four seven," he repeats. "Into the side I called half." A long breath. "Okay. Monday. And hey." A pause with forty years of flying in it. "Good stop."<<elseif $waltPlan is "text">>You send the thread three lines of numbers and no adjectives. Priya replies with a single word: <em>"Yikes."</em> Walt's reply arrives as you're climbing back in: <em>"Noted. Monday. Coffee's on me."</em> For Walt, that's a signed confession.<<else>>You write it in the log under his note, gallons by the meter, both sides, dated and timed. The numbers sit there on the page directly beneath "right at half, should be close," and no commentary you could add would say it better. Monday's meeting will read itself.<</if>>

The second leg is fifty-two minutes of two fat tanks and one quiet cockpit. Elena's door at 12:25 Mountain, an hour and change past the promise, four-something hours before her alarm. She pauses on the step.

"So that's what careful looks like from the inside," she says. "Huh. It mostly looks like gas station snacks." She holds up the jerky she bought from the vending machine at the empty pilot lounge, toasts you with it, and goes inside.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>At Ozona the panel handed you a genuinely mixed picture: a fuel-flow gauge reading thirsty, a quantity gauge with a documented lying habit reading low, a totalizer reading serene, a note saying half, and nothing aboard able to break the tie. You landed at a dark, sleeping airport with both engines running fine, and let a fuel pump's meter settle the argument. It ruled against the comfortable story: 11.8 gallons remained in the right tank, and the "watch it" option had about an hour left in it, with the dry point landing somewhere in the descent.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>This is the counterintuitive move that looks like weakness and is the whole skill: interrupting a working flight, backwards off the plan, to convert an estimate into a measurement. Every pressure in the cockpit argued against it, all of them social and none of them aerodynamic. The key discrimination you made at Ozona was between instruments with incentives and instruments without: the totalizer repeats whatever it was told at the ramp, the note repeats Walt's optimism, but fuel flow is measured at the engine, and it was the one gauge with no stake in the outcome. You believed the ugliest credible number, which is what that phrase is for.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Exactly this. A precautionary landing with both engines running is the cheapest insurance in aviation: twenty minutes, a card swipe, and certainty. The splash in San Antonio treated the note's number. It couldn't treat the note's error, because nobody knew the error's size until a meter measured it. When information conflicts at night over empty country, land where the truth is sold by the gallon.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>An estimate argued with an estimate all night, and the meter settled it in ninety seconds. Buy the measurement while both propellers still turn.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readFlightPlan to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readMap to false>><<set $fuelLeft to 46.5>><<set $fuelRight to 26.5>><<set $toppedOff to false>><<set $splashed to false>><<set $waltTexted to false>><<set $d2 to "">><<set $fuelSeen to false>><<set $rightSecured to false>><<set $featherFast to false>><<set $restored to false>><<set $airstart to false>><<set $declared to "none">><<set $crossfeedState to "normal">><<set $inversion to false>><<set $speedScare to false>><<set $headsDown to false>><<set $restumble to false>><<set $doubleScare to false>><<set $divert to "">><<set $seq to "">><<set $waltPlan to "">><<set $ground to "">><<set $backstop to false>><<set $leanChase to false>><<set $mgdSwitch to false>><<set $stab to "">><</link>>
</div>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: End_ELP_Relight [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: relight over the city's doorstep"])>>
The FBO ramp at midnight has a way of making everything that just happened feel implausible. The Seneca ticks and cools. The fuel truck's meter, summoned for the morning, will eventually report the right tank bone dry and the left holding fourteen, every drop of the evening's remaining fuel in one wing, exactly as you flew it.

Elena doesn't say anything until the seatbelts are off. Then: "At the gas stop in San Antonio. The quick one. Was that this?" You tell her the truth, that tonight will take some arithmetic to answer honestly, and that you intend to do the arithmetic. "Good," she says. "Show me too. I was there for the data collection."

She's home by 12:30, five hours before the alarm, and her text the next afternoon reads: <em>Shift survived. Kiddo #3 says hi. You owe me one boring flight.</em>

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>The quick splash in San Antonio bought the right tank about fifty extra minutes, and the flight needed about sixty. The shortfall came due at the worst address on the route: descending, at night, thirty-four hundred feet over the dark shelf east of El Paso. When it came due, you read it correctly in seconds, fed the windmilling engine from the left wing, and had it back before the situation could become one. <<if $seq is "arrTold">>You also put Approach in the loop before troubleshooting, which cleared the path to the runway while you worked.<</if>> The landing was normal. The margins around it were not.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>Two decisions bracket this ending. At Ozona, the fuel-flow discrepancy offered you the whole answer, 11.4 gallons an hour of it, and "within instrument slop" won because it asked nothing of the schedule. That's continuation bias wearing a lab coat. At the failure, the training held: diagnose before you secure. A pilot who feathers first at 3,400 AGL is committed to a single-engine night arrival; you spent three seconds on the fuel panel instead and got the engine back. The gap between those two versions of you, the one who waved at the number and the one who read the panel cold, is the gap this scenario is about.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Partial fills fix notes, not distributions: adding "about ten" to an estimated tank yields an estimated tank. The moment the JPI showed real burn above plan, the honest move was to re-run the dry-point arithmetic and act on the ugly answer while a lit runway sat twenty miles ahead. Failing that, exactly what you did at the surge: boost, crossfeed, three seconds. The engine was never sick. It was never anything but thirsty.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>A gallon number that doesn't match the plan is a countdown until proven otherwise. Ten gallons of "close enough" moved this failure from a fuel stop to final approach.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readFlightPlan to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readMap to false>><<set $fuelLeft to 46.5>><<set $fuelRight to 26.5>><<set $toppedOff to false>><<set $splashed to false>><<set $waltTexted to false>><<set $d2 to "">><<set $fuelSeen to false>><<set $rightSecured to false>><<set $featherFast to false>><<set $restored to false>><<set $airstart to false>><<set $declared to "none">><<set $crossfeedState to "normal">><<set $inversion to false>><<set $speedScare to false>><<set $headsDown to false>><<set $restumble to false>><<set $doubleScare to false>><<set $divert to "">><<set $seq to "">><<set $waltPlan to "">><<set $ground to "">><<set $backstop to false>><<set $leanChase to false>><<set $mgdSwitch to false>><<set $stab to "">><</link>>
</div>
