:: End_ELP_ArrOEI [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: one prop still, one runway used"])>>
The fire crew chief walks the airplane with you afterward, flashlight tracing the feathered blades, and asks what happened. "Fuel starvation," you say, and watch him relax the particular half-inch that means <em>oh, one of those</em>. He has seen one of those before. Everyone who works a crash truck long enough has.

The mechanic's verdict tomorrow will take four minutes and cost $180: nothing wrong. Tank was dry. The right engine will start on the first blade once it's fed, and idle there sounding faintly embarrassed on everyone's behalf.

Elena waits for the paperwork, watches you sign things, and says, on the drive home, "You went full checklist robot back there. It was weirdly reassuring." A pause. "The part before that, where the gauge argued with the plan for an hour? Less reassuring." She's home by 12:45. The porch light stays on a beat after the door closes, like the house is thinking it over.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>The splash-and-estimate fuel plan came up about ten minutes short, and the right engine starved on the arrival. You treated it as an engine failure rather than a fuel problem: identify, verify, feather, declare, and a disciplined single-engine landing on 26L with equipment standing by. The execution from feather to touchdown was solid. The diagnosis window before the feather, three seconds of fuel-panel reading at an altitude that comfortably allowed it, went unused, and a restorable engine crossed the airport fence as a monument.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>Feathering at 3,400 AGL descending is a defensible reflex and an incomplete one. The signature in front of you, fuel flow at zero, a pegged quantity needle, an opposite tank an eighth from full, spelled starvation, and starvation is the one engine failure that undoes itself in seconds when fuel arrives. The deeper error lived an hour back at Ozona, where a measured 11.4 gallons an hour lost the argument to a schedule. Credit where due: once committed, you flew the single-engine arrival as a commitment, declared without hedging, and never flirted with a go-around.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Altitude permitting, diagnose before you secure: boost pump and crossfeed cost five seconds and are fully reversible, while the feather, in an airplane with no unfeathering accumulators, is a decision you keep. And the arithmetic habit upstream is the real fix. A fuel-flow number above plan is a new dry-point calculation, done immediately, believed over the totalizer, acted on while the good options are still twenty miles ahead instead of behind.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>Diagnose before you secure. A thirsty engine restarts in seconds. A feathered one is a commitment, and at night on an arrival, it's a commitment you make for both of you.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readFlightPlan to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readMap to false>><<set $fuelLeft to 46.5>><<set $fuelRight to 26.5>><<set $toppedOff to false>><<set $splashed to false>><<set $waltTexted to false>><<set $d2 to "">><<set $fuelSeen to false>><<set $rightSecured to false>><<set $featherFast to false>><<set $restored to false>><<set $airstart to false>><<set $declared to "none">><<set $crossfeedState to "normal">><<set $inversion to false>><<set $speedScare to false>><<set $headsDown to false>><<set $restumble to false>><<set $doubleScare to false>><<set $divert to "">><<set $seq to "">><<set $waltPlan to "">><<set $ground to "">><<set $backstop to false>><<set $leanChase to false>><<set $mgdSwitch to false>><<set $stab to "">><</link>>
</div>
