:: End_ELP_Managed [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: the managed distribution"])>>
The shutdown flow ends with both fuel selectors sitting at ON, which tonight required actual thought, and the little ritual feels like closing out a chess game you barely remember agreeing to play.

<<if $mgdSwitch>>Elena unbuckles and points at the pedestal. "The thing I remembered on final. That was important, wasn't it. Like, actually."

"It would've been fine tonight. The tank it was pointed at had fuel." You look at the selectors a moment longer. "The last tank it was pointed at didn't. Same lever, same me."<<else>>Elena watches you initial the fuel log and asks what the X-FEED detent actually did tonight. You explain it in one sentence, the selector belongs to the engine and points its straw, and she nods slowly. "So it's an IV line with a stopcock. Why didn't you just say that."<</if>>

Home at 11:55 Mountain, twenty-five minutes over the promise. Sunday's text from the hospital: <em>All kiddos accounted for. Your gas gauge drama better be resolved by Thanksgiving.</em> The shop appointment for the injectors is Tuesday. You made it yourself, before bed.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>At Ozona you split the difference between diverting and hoping: you used the crossfeed for exactly what it is, plumbing that points an engine at the other wing, rested the suspect tank on the fat one for forty minutes, and re-fed it for the arrival. The distribution problem never got a vote. <<if $mgdSwitch>>The plan's one hook, the switch-back, nearly slipped through a busy arrival and surfaced at the GUMPS check on final, harmless only because the tank behind the selector had fuel this time.<<else>>You ran the switch-back at top of descent exactly as briefed, and the hook never got its chance.<</if>> The airplane landed with usable fuel in both wings and a squawk sheet entry that has graduated into a shop appointment.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>This worked because the mental model was exact. Crossfeed-as-insurance is the same lever that, inverted under stress, has starved good engines in this exact airplane type, and the difference between tool and trap is knowing which engine's straw you're moving and where the fuel actually is. Note the structure of what you built, though: a plan with a required future action, at night, in an arrival environment engineered to eat future actions. <<if $mgdSwitch>>It very nearly did. The catch came from a briefed passenger and a disciplined GUMPS habit, which is to say, from redundancy you'd installed earlier.<<else>>Your top-of-descent flow caught the hook because you put the hook where a flow would find it. That's system design, not luck.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Managing distribution in flight is legitimate systems work when the numbers are run and the model is cold. The comparison worth filing: the fuel stop at Fort Stockton would have solved the same problem with zero hooks and one receipt. In-flight management kept the schedule and carried a dependency; the ground stop spends the schedule and carries none. Knowing which trade you're making, and saying the hook out loud to another human, is what made this version airmanship instead of improvisation.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>Crossfeed moves fuel burn, never fuel. It's a sharp tool with exactly one correct grip, and every plan built on it carries a hook you must not drop.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readFlightPlan to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readMap to false>><<set $fuelLeft to 46.5>><<set $fuelRight to 26.5>><<set $toppedOff to false>><<set $splashed to false>><<set $waltTexted to false>><<set $d2 to "">><<set $fuelSeen to false>><<set $rightSecured to false>><<set $featherFast to false>><<set $restored to false>><<set $airstart to false>><<set $declared to "none">><<set $crossfeedState to "normal">><<set $inversion to false>><<set $speedScare to false>><<set $headsDown to false>><<set $restumble to false>><<set $doubleScare to false>><<set $divert to "">><<set $seq to "">><<set $waltPlan to "">><<set $ground to "">><<set $backstop to false>><<set $leanChase to false>><<set $mgdSwitch to false>><<set $stab to "">><</link>>
</div>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: SE_Secured [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Right engine feathered and secured"])>>
<<if $featherFast>>Your hands run the drill the way the drill was built to run. Mixtures up. Props up. Throttles up. Flaps checked, gear checked. Dead foot, dead engine: right. Verify: right throttle to idle, no change in anything. Right prop lever back, back, through the detent into FEATHER, and the windmilling disk out there shudders, slows, and knifes into four still blades. Mixture cut. Boost off. Right selector OFF. Cowl flap closed. Forty seconds, maybe less. Your multi instructor would have applauded.

As your hand comes off the pedestal, your eye finally crosses the gauge it skipped on the way by: right fuel flow. Zero. It was zero before you touched a thing. Wherever that fact wants to go, it files itself under later.<<else>>You work it as a procedure instead of a reflex. Identify: dead foot says right. Verify: right throttle to idle, nothing changes. Feather: the right prop lever back through the detent, and the gray disk out there shudders, slows, and knifes into four still blades. Mixture cut, boost off, right selector OFF, cowl flap closed, trim in.<</if>>

The Seneca settles onto one engine like it read its own brochure. Left engine to max continuous, blue radial plus ten, and the turbo holds what a normally aspirated twin would be trading away: altitude. A slow sag to ninety-six hundred and then the VSI levels. The airplane flies fine. It just flies committed, because there are no unfeathering accumulators on this airplane, and that prop does not come back with a lever.

Albuquerque gets the update: right engine secured and feathered, maintaining ninety-six hundred, two souls.

Elena's voice is careful. "Is it going to stay up?"

"It's built for this. It'll hold altitude all night."

"Okay." A pause. "Then I'm going to sit here and believe you."

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Fuel Panel, Secured</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Leave the plumbing alone. The running engine is drinking from the wing that has all the fuel, and the feathered side's selector is OFF where the flow put it." "SE_D5_Divert">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Left the fuel panel alone, OEI"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Single-engine flight is exactly what the crossfeed exists for. Set the good engine up on X-FEED so the system carries it for the long haul." "SE_Scare">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Moved the good engine's selector to X-FEED"])>>
  <<set $inversion to true>><<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Try the air start. Starter-assist unfeather, fed through the crossfeed. If it was fuel, you can have the second engine back." "SE_Airstart">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Attempted the starter-assist unfeather"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: SE_Scare [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The good engine starts to die"])>>
The left selector comes out of ON, across the gate, into X-FEED. The panel looks more single-engine now, somehow. Configured. Deliberate.

For forty seconds nothing happens, because forty seconds is how long the fuel already in the lines lasts.

Then the left fuel flow needle sags. The engine, the only engine, surges, catches itself, surges again, and the Seneca yaws into the dead side with a motion you feel in your back teeth. The manifold pressure starts down. Elena says your name once, quietly, like she's checking it still works.

The left selector is pointing the left engine's straw at the right wing. The right wing is a bottle of air.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: Forty Seconds In</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Read the panel out loud like you wrote it: left selector on X-FEED means left engine drinking the empty wing. Selector back to ON. Boost. Now." "SE_Recovered">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Caught the inversion, selector back to ON"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. It has to be the pump or something in the line, the selector is set up the way single-engine work wants it. Cycle the boost, work the mixture, coax it." "Glide_Both">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Troubleshot around the selector while it died"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: SE_Recovered [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The good engine recovers"])>>
<<set $doubleScare to true>>
Selector back to ON. Boost pump on. The left engine drinks air for one more endless second, then fuel, and comes back with a surge and a snarl and settles to its work like nothing happened.

Your shirt is stuck to your back. Elena has both hands wrapped around the cake box strap, white-knuckled, protecting the one thing on this airplane she can protect.

The crossfeed valve has exactly one correct mental model, and at 10:30 at night with one engine feathered, you just met the wrong one. The selector belongs to the engine. It points that engine's straw. That is all it has ever done.

"Say something," Elena says.

"The airplane's fine. That one was me. It won't happen again."

She nods, once, and believes you, which is somehow the heaviest thing in the cockpit.

<<goto "SE_D5_Divert">>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: SE_Airstart [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Starter-assist unfeather"])>>
<<set $airstart to true>><<set $restored to true>><<set $rightSecured to false>><<set $crossfeedState to "rightFromLeft">>
No accumulators means the starter does the work. You set it up like a surgeon laying out instruments: right selector to X-FEED, drinking the left wing. Right boost pump on. Mixture rich. Prop lever to mid-range. Throttle cracked. Then the starter, held, while the panel lights sag yellow and the alternator on the left engine grunts under the load.

The feathered blades lean, lean, and swing flat. The prop windmills. The starter lets go, the windmill spins up, and the TSIO fires, coughs blue in the dark somewhere behind the cowl, and runs. You warm it gently, a thousand RPM, then bring it into sync, minding the turbo like a kettle.

The whole production costs eight hundred feet, five minutes, most of a battery's dignity, and one long look from Elena, who watched the propeller come back to life the way people watch defibrillators.

Both engines run. Both drink from the left wing, through the one selector in X-FEED. The totalizer says 19.5. El Paso is 128 miles into the wind. Fort Stockton is 52 behind, wind helping. Pecos, 20 off the right rear, still has no weather and no long runway tonight.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: Second Engine, Second Chance</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Take the gift and turn around. Fort Stockton, fuel, and the rest of the night gets boring." "Divert_FST_Turn">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D5: airstart, then turned back for fuel"])>>
  <<set $divert to "KFST">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Press for El Paso with the minimum fuel call made and the system watching over you." "Cruise_KELP_Advise">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D5: airstart, continued with min fuel advisory"])>>
  <<set $declared to "min">>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Press for El Paso without ceremony. Two running engines is a normal airplane." "Cruise_KELP_Quiet">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D5: airstart, continued quietly"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: SE_D5_Divert [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The single-engine divert decision"])>>
<<if $doubleScare>>With your heart rate somewhere back near the yellow arc, the<<else>>The<</if>> situation steadies into numbers. One engine, feathered and committed. One engine, strong, fed by the only wing with fuel in it, about twenty gallons, an hour and three quarters at this power. Ninety-six hundred feet over terrain that runs twenty-seven hundred. The panel timer you're not using counts nothing.

El Paso: 134 miles on the nose, into the wind, on one engine. Call it an hour and ten. Airline runways, crash trucks, a tower that never sleeps, and your own bed at the end of it. Fort Stockton: 48 miles behind, wind helping, eighteen minutes and a long straight-in to 7,500 feet of asphalt with nobody on it and a pump that takes cards.

Albuquerque asks the question controllers ask when they're inviting you to say the word: "Six two Charlie, say intentions, and advise if you require assistance."

Elena is looking at the side of your face. "Whatever you're deciding," she says, "decide it like I'm asleep. Don't factor me. I mean it."

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: One Engine, Two Doors</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Declare the emergency and take the near door: Fort Stockton, eighteen minutes, wind at your back." "Approach_SE_FST">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D5: declared, diverted Fort Stockton"])>>
  <<set $declared to "emergency">><<set $divert to "KFST">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Declare the emergency and continue to El Paso: the long runway, the equipment, the services, everything a sick airplane could want." "Cruise_SE_West">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D5: declared, continued OEI to El Paso"])>>
  <<set $declared to "emergency">><<set $divert to "KELP">>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Fort Stockton, but no declaration. It's a precautionary landing, not a crisis, and the paperwork can stay in its drawer." "Approach_SE_FST">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D5: diverted quietly to Fort Stockton"])>>
  <<set $divert to "KFST">>
<</link>>

<<link "D. Continue to El Paso as an abnormal, not an emergency. The airplane is stable, the book says she'll hold altitude all night, and declaring changes nothing about the flying." "Cruise_SE_West">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D5: continued OEI, no declaration"])>>
  <<set $divert to "KELP">><<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Approach_SE_FST [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Single-engine arrival, Fort Stockton"])>>
<<if $declared is "emergency">>"Six two Charlie, roger, understand declaring emergency, cleared direct Fort Stockton, descend at your discretion. ASOS one one eight point five two five. I'll have the county advised. Souls and fuel?" Two souls. An hour forty of fuel. The county, you both know, is one sheriff's deputy who will drive out and watch your landing light come down the black.<<else>>"Six two Charlie, roger, cleared direct Fort Stockton, descend your discretion, ASOS one one eight point five two five. Advise if you require assistance." The offer hangs there, polite, unused.<</if>>

You keep the altitude in your pocket most of the way, because altitude is the only spare part you have left, and let it out on a long, shallow, planned slide. ASOS: wind one six zero at six, altimeter three zero zero four. Runway 12. Seven clicks on 122.8 and the MIRL steps up out of the desert, two amber rails and a PAPI already burning.

You brief it out loud, mostly for your own ears: "Gear down at the fix. Flaps when the runway's made. This one lands. There is no go-around on one engine at night, so we don't plan one."

Blue radial all the way down final. Two white, two red. Over the threshold at ninety-five, power off, and the Seneca touches down on the left main first, straightens, and rolls out long and easy with one propeller turning and one standing still like a monument to the evening.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "Taxi in on one engine and shut down under the sodium light." "End_SE_FST">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed OEI at Fort Stockton"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_SE_West [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The long single-engine hour"])>>
<<if $declared is "emergency">>The frequency reorganizes itself around you. "Six two Charlie, roger, emergency aircraft, cleared direct El Paso, altitude your discretion. Equipment will be standing by. Advise any change." Somewhere ahead, fire trucks are rolling to positions with your tail number written on a pad.<<else>>"Six two Charlie, roger, direct El Paso, advise any change in status." The system files you where you asked to be filed: unremarkable.<</if>>

An hour and ten on one engine is long division performed in the dark. You hold ninety-six hundred, blue radial plus ten, cowl flap trimmed so the left engine's temperatures sit in the green and stay there. Every ten minutes the totalizer surrenders two more gallons. The feathered prop out the right window catches the instrument glow, four blades of absolute stillness, and you catch yourself checking it the way you'd check on a sleeping child.

Elena talks you across the empty miles about nothing at all, in a voice with a professional calm you recognize from a hundred family emergencies that were never yours before. "Tell me when to worry," she says once.

"Not yet."

"Okay. I'll wait."

The Guadalupes pass somewhere north, invisible. Then the bowl of El Paso light comes over the earth's curve, and Approach turns you loose downhill.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Arrival Geometry</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Ask for the long, flat, boring setup: a wide turn to a ten-mile final for 26L, gear and flaps on your own schedule." "End_SE_ELP">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Took the long stabilized final"])>>
  <<set $stab to "long">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Take the short approach Approach offers to beat the inbound airline flow: keep the speed, slot inside, save ten minutes of one-engine exposure." "Approach_SE_High">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Accepted the tight short approach"])>>
  <<set $stab to "tight">>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Approach_SE_High [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["High and hot on short final"])>>
The short approach saves the ten minutes and spends them all back at once. The turn to final comes tight and close-in, and the Seneca arrives on the glidepath's doorstep high, fast, and unamused: four white lights on the PAPI, a hundred and fifteen knots, one engine at idle and one giving everything, gear down, half flaps, the runway numbers sliding under the nose with 9,025 feet of concrete stretched out beyond them and a 737 somewhere behind you on the arrival.

Tower: "Seneca six two Charlie, wind variable at three, runway two six left, cleared to land."

The float begins. A thousand feet of runway. Two thousand. The airplane is flying itself onto the far half of a very long runway, ugly, long, and absolutely landable.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: Ugly or Again</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Put it down. Long is fine on nine thousand feet. Fly it onto the pavement, brake straight, take the ugly." "End_SE_ELP">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed long on 26L"])>>
  <<set $stab to "tight-landed">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Go around and do it properly. One clean circuit, a stabilized final, a landing you'd sign your name to." "End_SE_GoAround">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Attempted the single-engine go-around"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Glide_Both [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Both engines quiet"])>>
The boost pump cycles. The mixture goes rich, lean, rich. The left engine takes none of it personally and dies anyway, all the way, the propeller slowing to a windmill, and then the Seneca is a nine-thousand-pound glider with one prop feathered, one prop turning uselessly in the airstream, and a cockpit quiet enough to hear Elena breathing.

The panel keeps its counsel. Left selector: X-FEED. Right selector: OFF. Right tank: empty since 10:21. Left tank: twenty gallons of fuel, sealed away from both engines by two levers set exactly where hands under stress put them.

Ninety-four hundred feet. Terrain twenty-seven hundred. The math offers you about ten miles of glide and one decision at a time. Off the right rear quarter, twenty miles out, the Pecos beacon strobes white-green, tiny and regular. South, the interstate's bead of truck lights. Below, scattered across the black, the orange breath of oilfield flares.

"What do I do," Elena says. Not panicked. Asking for a job.

<div class="decision-heading">Decision: The Glide</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Fuel panel, out loud, like you're reading it to a student: left selector is on X-FEED, drinking the empty wing. Put it back to ON. Boost. Give it three seconds." "Glide_Relight">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Read the panel aloud, found the inversion"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Mayday, and commit to the ground while you own the geometry: the lease road by the nearest flare, into the wind, gear down, lights on." "Glide_Commit">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Committed to the off-airport landing"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Stretch for the Pecos beacon. Twenty miles, a real runway, and the wind quartering behind you. Beacons have pulled sicker airplanes home." "Glide_Stretch">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Stretched the glide for Pecos"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Glide_Relight [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Relight in the glide"])>>
<<set $doubleScare to true>>
"Left selector," you say out loud, to the airplane, to Elena, to the examiner who lives in your head, "is on crossfeed. Crossfeed points it at the right wing. The right wing is empty." Your hand moves the lever across the gate to ON. "Boost."

One second. Two. The windmilling left prop drags fuel up the line. Three.

The engine catches with a bang and a snarl, and power comes back into the airframe like blood into a sleeping limb. You let the nose down, buy back the blue radial, and level at eight thousand two hundred with one engine running, one feathered, and roughly nineteen gallons of extremely well-earned humility in the left wing.

Elena lets out a breath that has edges on it. On the frequency, Albuquerque is asking, for the second time, whether six two Charlie reads.

"Six two Charlie's back," you say. "We're back."

<<goto "SE_D5_Divert">>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Glide_Commit [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Mayday and the lease road"])>>
"Mayday, mayday, mayday, Seneca seven four six two Charlie, dual engine failure, niner thousand, two souls, we are landing on a road."

"Six two Charlie, mayday copied." The controller's voice goes very smooth, the way they train for. "Position copied. Emergency services are being notified. Winds Fort Stockton one six zero at six. Frequency is yours."

You fly the glide like a checkride: ninety knots, the nearest flare off the nose, and beneath it, straightening as you descend, a pale caliche lease road running long and straight toward a well pad, into the wind or near enough. You brief Elena in short sentences. Belt tight. Door cracked on short final. Head down, arms braced. She repeats it all back like a nurse taking a verbal order, word for word, twice.

Five hundred feet. The road holds steady in the landing light, washboard and all. Gear down. You pick the spot between a cattle guard and the dark.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "Fly it all the way to the ground." "End_Glide_Road">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Forced landing, lease road"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Glide_Stretch [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Stretching for the beacon"])>>
You point the nose at the white-green strobe and tell the airplane it's going to Pecos. Best glide, wind quartering behind, twenty miles to pavement and about ten miles of altitude in the bank. The arithmetic doesn't improve with attention. You give it attention anyway.

The beacon strobes. It does not grow.

Six thousand. The flares crawl past below, each one a road you are choosing not to use, each one further behind. Elena is silent, both hands on the cake box, watching the altimeter because you keep watching it.

Four thousand. The beacon has become two lights, a beacon and something near it, still eight miles out. The ground below has gone from options to mesquite.

Two hundred above the scrub, the landing light finds a road, off the nose, crossing at forty degrees. It is the first road in three miles. It will require a turn.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "Make the turn." "End_Fatal">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The low turn to the road"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: End_SE_FST [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: OEI landing at Fort Stockton"])>>
You shut down under the sodium light and the silence comes in like a tide. <<if $declared is "emergency">>Ten minutes later a Pecos County sheriff's truck rolls slowly up the ramp, no lights, and a deputy in a canvas jacket leans out. "Y'all the emergency? Dispatch said watch for a plane with one propeller." He looks at the feathered blades for a while, says "huh," and stays to hold a flashlight while you fuel, which turns out to be the exact assistance the situation required.<<else>>Nobody comes, because nobody knows. The field is yours: one sodium light, one card reader, one airplane with one still propeller, and the entire audible universe consisting of a truck shifting gears out on the interstate.<</if>>

The pumps take your personal card on the second try. Elena stands at the edge of the light with her arms crossed, watching you fuel both wings, saying nothing for a long time. On the phone, Walt listens to the whole story and is quiet for five seconds, which for Walt is a eulogy. "The note said half," he starts, and then stops himself. "Monday. All three of us. I'll bring the coffee."

You do not fly home tonight. The Sandstone Inn has rooms, and tomorrow a mechanic from Odessa will run the right engine on the ground, find nothing wrong with it at all, and charge you $340 to confirm the tank was simply empty.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>The right engine starved and quit. You committed to feathering a restorable engine<<if $featherFast>> within the first minute, before any diagnosis<</if>>, which turned a ten-second fuel problem into a genuine single-engine night flight. <<if $doubleScare>>The crossfeed inversion then nearly took the good engine too, and you caught it inside the correction window. <</if>>From there your execution was sound: disciplined single-engine cruise, the near airport over the far one, altitude hoarded, a no-go-around brief said out loud, and a clean OEI landing at a dark field.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>The pivotal moment was the feather. Identify-verify-feather is drilled until it feels like the whole answer, but the drill exists for an engine that is broken, and this one was thirsty: fuel flow at zero, a dry gauge, a fat tank on the other wing, every sign pointing at starvation for anyone with a spare five seconds to look. Feathering is a committed act in an airplane with no unfeathering accumulators. The macho pull here is subtle, the pride of executing the emergency crisply rather than asking whether it was the right emergency. <<if $declared is "emergency">>Declaring was correct and cost you nothing but a deputy's flashlight, which was a bargain.<<else>>Not declaring cost you nothing tonight, but notice what it was protecting: not the flight, just the story about the flight.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Diagnose before you secure. A windmilling engine that died of starvation restarts in seconds once fuel arrives through the crossfeed, and the ten seconds spent reading fuel flow, gauges, and selector positions are the cheapest insurance in multi-engine flying. Once feathered, everything you did is the model: Vyse discipline, the near door over the familiar one, and treating a single-engine night approach as a one-shot arrival. That last brief, "this one lands," is worth stealing for real life.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>Feather the engine the diagnosis convicts, not the one the drill is fastest against. In a light twin, the ten-second look is the difference between an anecdote and an emergency.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readFlightPlan to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readMap to false>><<set $fuelLeft to 46.5>><<set $fuelRight to 26.5>><<set $toppedOff to false>><<set $splashed to false>><<set $waltTexted to false>><<set $d2 to "">><<set $fuelSeen to false>><<set $rightSecured to false>><<set $featherFast to false>><<set $restored to false>><<set $airstart to false>><<set $declared to "none">><<set $crossfeedState to "normal">><<set $inversion to false>><<set $speedScare to false>><<set $headsDown to false>><<set $restumble to false>><<set $doubleScare to false>><<set $divert to "">><<set $seq to "">><<set $ground to "">><<set $backstop to false>><<set $leanChase to false>><<set $mgdSwitch to false>><<set $stab to "">><</link>>
</div>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: End_SE_ELP [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: OEI landing at El Paso"])>>
<<if $stab is "long">>The long final is ten minutes of geometry and patience, gear at the fix, flaps when the runway is guaranteed, the PAPI held at two-and-two like it owes you money. The touchdown is so ordinary it's almost disappointing.<<else>>You put it down long and ugly and entirely on purpose, wheels kissing at midfield with a mile of concrete still ahead, brakes steady, nosewheel straight. Nobody scores style points at night on one engine. Rollout complete with pavement to spare.<</if>> <<if $declared is "emergency">>The trucks pace you down the runway edge, lights turning, and peel off when you call it good on the rollout. The tower's "welcome to El Paso" has actual warmth in it.<<else>>The tower, who knew only what you told them, clears the next arrival before you're off the runway. The fire trucks you didn't ask for stay parked, which you notice, and file away to think about later.<</if>>

The feathered prop gets a long look from the FBO line crew. Elena is home by 12:15, five hours before her alarm. At the door she says, "That was the real thing tonight, wasn't it," and when you nod she nods back, once, and goes in without another word, which is how nurses hug.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>A starved right engine was feathered rather than diagnosed and restored<<if $doubleScare>>, the crossfeed inversion then briefly threatened the left engine before you caught it<</if>>, and you flew more than an hour of single-engine night cruise to the destination, past a serviceable airport eighteen minutes away. The approach <<if $stab is "long">>was flown on your terms, long and stable, and the landing was routine<<elseif $stab is "tight-landed">>arrived high and hot off the short approach, and you made the correct one-engine call: take the long landing the 9,025-foot runway was built to absorb<<else>>worked out<</if>>. Everyone is fine. The exposure was real.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>Two decisions carried the risk. The feather converted a restorable engine into a committed single-engine airplane. The continue converted an eighteen-minute problem into a seventy-minute one. The arguments for El Paso were real: equipment, runway, services, home. But single-engine cruise is a state where the next failure has no backup, and minutes of exposure are the currency. <<if $declared is "emergency">>You spent the exposure with the system fully briefed and equipment waiting, which is how that bet should be placed if it must be placed.<<else>>You spent it anonymously, saving yourself a conversation and spending the one resource ATC can't give back: their chance to prepare for you.<</if>> <<if $stab is "tight-landed">>Accepting the slam-dunk approach was the night's last unnecessary bet, and landing long instead of going around was the right way to lose it.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Diagnosis first: fuel flow zero plus a dry gauge plus a fat opposite tank spells starvation, and the crossfeed restores it in seconds. Feathered anyway, the model answer is the near airport, declared, altitude kept high and spent late. And on one engine, the approach is a one-way street: a light twin at nearly 4,000 feet of field elevation, gear out, one windmilling start away from Vmc work in the dark, does not go around. Long landings on long runways are free.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>On one engine, distance is risk and the go-around does not exist. Fly to the nearest honest runway and land on the first try, ugly if necessary.</p>
</div>
