:: End_SE_GoAround [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: the single-engine go-around"])>>
Full power on the left engine. Flaps to ten. The nose comes up and the Seneca stops descending, which is not the same as climbing.

Field elevation 3,962. Density altitude tonight around 5,300. One engine giving its whole heart through a turbocharger, one feathered, gear cycling up too slowly, and the airspeed sitting two knots above blue line with the VSI needle trembling on either side of zero. The runway lights slide behind. The dark off the departure end is not empty: it has a localizer antenna platform in it, and beyond that the airport's perimeter ground rising gently toward the boundary.

The airplane settles. Not dramatically. Ten feet a second, the mush of an airplane being asked for a performance that was never in the book at this weight, this altitude, this temperature. You hold blue line because there is nothing else to hold, and the Seneca meets the ground two hundred yards past the runway end, gear half-retracted, sliding on its belly through the dirt in a long, roaring, sparking hiss that ends with one wing low against the perimeter road embankment.

The silence after is total. Elena's voice, shaking, comes from very far away: "Out. We're getting out."

You are both standing in the dirt, whole, unbroken, watching the fire trucks arrive at the airplane you almost flew home, when your phone starts buzzing in your pocket. It's Walt. You don't answer it yet.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>After a starvation failure, a feather, and a long single-engine cruise, the arrival came unraveled: high and hot off a short approach, and instead of accepting a long landing on a 9,025-foot runway, you asked a one-engine Seneca for a go-around at a density altitude near 5,300 feet. The airplane gave you everything it had, which was level flight, briefly, and then it settled off the departure end. The airframe is destroyed. You and Elena walked away, which the energy management on final made possible even as the decision above it did not.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>The go-around is so deeply trained as the safe harbor that it takes deliberate multi-engine re-education to see when it stops being one. Single-engine, gear out, at altitude and weight, a light twin's "go-around" is a slow-motion arrival to terrain you didn't choose. The decision to accept the slam-dunk approach set the trap, and the perfectionism of "do it properly" sprang it. There was a boring correct answer sitting under the nose the whole time: a mile of unused concrete. The hazardous attitude here isn't recklessness. It's craftsmanship applied to the wrong problem.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Brief the single-engine approach as a commitment: this one lands. If the setup is bad, fix it early, refuse the tight geometry, ask for the long final, and if you still arrive high on a long runway, land long. The performance chart, not courage or skill, decides whether a single-engine go-around exists, and at this weight and density altitude it did not. The time to consult that chart is at the top of descent, not in the flare.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>A single-engine go-around is not a plan. It's a performance claim, and the airplane gets the final vote on whether it's true.</p>
</div>
