:: End_Glide_Road [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: the lease road"])>>
The Seneca arrives on the caliche doing ninety, flares in the landing light's gray cone, and touches down straighter than some of your runway landings. The washboard hammers the gear. A mesquite branch takes the left position light. The cattle guard passes under the nose with feet to spare, and the airplane rolls out and stops in the absolute middle of nowhere, upright, intact except for the nosewheel pant and its dignity, one propeller feathered and the other ticking down to stillness.

The flare a half mile away breathes orange against the dark. Elena unbuckles with careful hands. "Everyone out anyway," she says. "We can admire it from outside."

The oilfield crew truck finds you before the deputy does, two men in flame-resistant coveralls who have clearly decided this is the best night shift of their careers. Albuquerque Center, who watched your primary target stop moving and held their breath, gets a phone call from your cell that begins, "Six two Charlie is on the ground, two souls, zero injuries," and you can hear the sector exhale.

The airplane will leave the lease road in three weeks, on a truck, missing its wings temporarily and its right tank's mystery permanently: the recovery crew will drain 19.6 gallons out of the left wing.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>A starved engine was feathered instead of diagnosed. The crossfeed inversion then pointed the good engine at the empty tank, and troubleshooting focused everywhere except the selector until the left engine died too. Gliding, you made the decision that saved the night: mayday, commit early to a reachable lit surface, and fly a disciplined forced landing. The airplane is damaged and recoverable. You and Elena are unhurt. Nineteen point six gallons of fuel rode to the ground with you, sealed off by two lever positions.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>Three links forged this chain: feathering before diagnosing, inverting the crossfeed's logic under stress, and troubleshooting the boost pump while the selector sat wrong. Each was reasonable-feeling in the moment, and that is the lesson: the crossfeed valve has exactly one correct mental model, the selector belongs to the engine and points that engine's straw, and any fuzzier version of it will fail you precisely when you're too loaded to re-derive it. The decision that broke the chain deserves equal attention: committing to the road while altitude still bought geometry, instead of gambling the remaining glide on a distant beacon. That choice is why this debrief is being read in the second person.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Ten seconds of fuel-panel diagnosis at the first failure ends this story at Fort Stockton with a gas receipt. Failing that, the panel read aloud in the glide, selector by selector, restores the left engine with thousands of feet to spare. Failing that, exactly what you did: pick the surface early, into the wind, lit if the night offers it, and fly the airplane all the way through the arrival. A survivable off-airport landing is not a failure of airmanship. It's the system working with its last layer.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>When an engine dies with fuel on board, the selectors are guilty until proven innocent. Read them out loud, exactly as they sit, before you touch anything else.</p>
</div>
