:: End_Fatal [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: the turn"])>>
The road crosses the nose at forty degrees, two hundred feet down. The bank goes in, and then a little more, because the road is passing faster than the turn is coming around. The airspeed is at best glide, which was never meant to hold a steepening turn this close to the ground.

The stall horn sounds once.

The NTSB preliminary report is four paragraphs. It notes the dark night conditions, the fuel found in the left wing tank, the left fuel selector discovered in the crossfeed position, the right selector off, and the impact consistent with an aerodynamic stall in a left turn at low altitude. It reads, as these reports read, like weather: no villains, no adjectives, two fatalities, a familiar sequence laid out in the past tense for the pilots who will read it over coffee and think, quietly, that they would have caught it at the ramp.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>Every link connected. A lopsided fuel load accepted against a sticky gauge. A management plan dissolved by ordinary interruptions. A restorable engine feathered without diagnosis. The crossfeed inverted under stress, the good engine starved, the troubleshooting aimed at pumps instead of selectors. Then the glide was spent on a beacon twenty miles away instead of a surface ten minutes below, and the last two hundred feet were asked to hold a steepening turn that no best-glide speed can pay for. The airplane hit the ground flying-adjacent, in a stall, at night, with nineteen usable gallons aboard.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>No single decision here was exotic. Each one has been made by real pilots in real airplanes, and each was recoverable right up to the last. The pattern underneath them is continuation under stress: at every fork, the option that avoided admitting the situation, turning around, declaring, landing short, landing on dirt, felt like the strong choice. The beacon stretch is the purest form of it, trading a certain, survivable landing for a possible, perfect one. Fuel starvation accidents in twins almost never kill in the first act. They kill in the fourth, when the altitude is gone and the mental model still hasn't been corrected.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Any of four moves ends this story safely: per-side fuel math at the ramp, a ten-second diagnosis before the feather, the selector read aloud when the second engine faltered, or the early commit to the lease road with the mayday out and the geometry owned. The forced landing you accept at three thousand feet is nearly always survivable. The airport you almost reach is not.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>Never trade a landing you can make for one you might. The last link in a fuel-starvation chain is almost always a low-altitude turn toward hope.</p>
</div>
