:: End_FST_GoAgain [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: refueled and flew home"])>>
The second leg is the most boring fifty-two minutes of flying you have ever been grateful for. Both gauges agree all the way down their arcs. The crossfeed selector sits at ON like it never heard of tonight. El Paso rises out of the desert right on schedule, and the tower clears you to land on the first call.

Elena's door at 12:20, Mountain time. An hour and twenty past the promise. She hugs you in the driveway, holds it one extra beat, and says, "Next time I'm asking what the gauges say <em>before</em> we leave the party."

At 2:40 the next afternoon, after her shift, she texts: <em>Kiddo #3 came off CPAP today. Also I told the whole pod my brother turned the airplane around for gas like a responsible adult. They were disappointed it wasn't a better story.</em>

It was exactly the story you wanted it to be, by the width of one selector detent.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>The right engine quit from fuel starvation two hours and nine minutes into the flight, because the airplane left San Antonio with 46.5 gallons in one wing and 26.5 in the other, and the planning was done against the total. <<if $headsDown>>You went to the fuel panel with the airplane untended and let the speed decay nearly to blue line before recovering, but you<<else>>You<</if>> diagnosed a windmilling engine before committing to anything irreversible, restored it with crossfeed in seconds, ran the arithmetic honestly, and traded a reachable destination for a boring one. Then you finished the trip with fuel in both wings.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>Two decisions defined this outcome. The first was accepting the lopsided load with a plan to manage it aloft<<if $d2 is "memory">>, a plan that then dissolved into a rerouted clearance and a good story from the right seat<<else>>, a plan the night dismantled one interruption at a time despite your countermeasures<</if>>. That is how fuel starvation actually happens: not as recklessness, but as a reasonable-sounding plan plus a normal amount of disruption. The second was the turnback. With both engines running again, continuing felt natural and Fort Stockton felt like defeat. You weighed an hour of fuel against an hour and five of flying and refused the coin flip. That is the counterintuitive move this scenario exists to teach: landing short, backwards, at a dark field, while everything worked.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Twins demand per-side fuel math. A totalizer answers "how much," never "where," and 91.167 is satisfied by numbers that can still starve an engine if they're all in one wing. When an engine quits at cruise with fuel flow at zero and a fat tank on the other side, the high-skill move is the boring one: boost pump, crossfeed, ten seconds of patience. Feathering is for engines that are broken, not engines that are thirsty. And when the math gets thin, the nearest honest fuel beats the nearest familiar runway.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>The second engine doubles the systems knowledge required, not the safety margin. Fuel you cannot reach the runway with is measured per side, per hour, per honest number, and never by wishing.</p>
</div>
