:: End_FST_Overnight [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: overnight in Fort Stockton"])>>
The Sandstone Inn has two rooms, thin towels, and a lobby that smells like fifty years of coffee. Elena calls the unit at 5:00 a.m. and gets Dee, who has already juggled the assignment board. "Take the back half," Dee says. "Your brother did the right thing. Tell him the nurses said so."

You fly home at 6:30 into a tangerine sunrise, the desert soft and harmless-looking in the low light, both gauges agreeing. Elena watches out the window the whole way and doesn't sleep. On the El Paso ramp she stands by the wing for a second, pats the cowling of the right engine twice, the way she'd pat a large dog that bit someone once, and goes to work eleven hours after she meant to be in bed.

Walt is at the hangar Monday with tacos and a laminated card he made at an office store: <em>FUEL LOG ENTRIES: GALLONS PER SIDE, BY THE METER, NO ADJECTIVES.</em> It's the closest he'll come to an apology, and honestly, it's a good card.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>Fuel starvation stopped the right engine over the empty middle of Texas. You restored it with crossfeed, diverted back to Fort Stockton, refueled, and then made one more good decision that cost something: you refused to fly the last leg on top of two hours of adrenaline. Elena missed the start of her shift. The mission finished a day frayed, and everyone aboard finished it rested and alive.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>The chain that mattered ran through the fuel desk in San Antonio, where a totalizer number and a partner's adjective outvoted a gauge that was telling the truth. Everything after the engine quit was recovery, and the recovery was sound: diagnosis before commitment, an honest re-math, a turnback that felt like defeat and wasn't. The overnight call is the quiet star. The IMSAFE checklist doesn't have a box for "just relit an engine over a black desert," but stress is the S, and you scored it honestly when the pressure to redeem the night was at its peak.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Exactly this, one ramp decision earlier. The realistic cost of that ramp decision was never a crash. It was this: a covered shift, a colleague juggling a NICU board at 5 a.m., a sister who trusts you slightly differently now, and a partnership meeting with laminated cards. Most fuel-planning errors send the bill here, to the people around the pilot, and the bill is real even when the airplane is fine.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>The shortcut taken at the fuel pump always sends an invoice. The only thing decided later, in the air, is who pays it and in what currency.</p>
</div>
