:: End_ELP_MinFuel [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: landed KELP on minimum fuel"])>>
The fuel truck meets you at the FBO because Approach asked it to. The fueler sticks the nozzle in the left wing, then the right, and watches the meter spin past ninety gallons into a ninety-three-gallon system. He doesn't say anything. He writes the number on the ticket in careful block digits, the way people write numbers they intend to tell someone about later.

Elena is home by 11:40 Mountain, an hour behind the promise, five hours ahead of her alarm. She hugs you at the door. "Thank you for the part where you told them," she says. "The rest we're going to talk about after I sleep."

<<if $declared is "late">>Approach's parting words are still in your ear from the handoff: "Good outcome, six two Charlie. Sooner's better, next time." Nothing on paper. Just a sentence you'll be rehearing on quiet legs for years.<<else>>You sit in the parked car a minute doing the arithmetic one last time. Sixty-one minutes flown. About fifty-eight aboard when you chose it. The difference between this ending and a very different one was a number smaller than the gauge error.<</if>>

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>After the relight you continued to El Paso with roughly 22 gallons aboard, all of it in the left wing, feeding both engines through the crossfeed. <<if $declared is "late">>You told no one until the arrival sequence made the corner of the box visible, then told the truth late and got priority immediately.<<else>>You told the system the truth in the two words built for it, minimum fuel, and the system kept the path clear.<</if>> <<if $restumble>>You also returned the right selector to ON on the way in, re-starved the engine from a placard reflex, and re-learned the crossfeed model with a second relight.<</if>> You landed with about three gallons: fifteen minutes of flying, none of it in the tank the placard prefers.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>The pivotal decision was continuing at all. An hour of fuel against an hour and five of night flying is not a margin, it's a wager where the counterparty is the wind. Fort Stockton, twenty-two minutes behind you with a working pump, was the honest answer, and the pull of the destination, the schedule, and the already-late promise is exactly the shape of get-there-itis in its natural habitat. What you did right within the wager mattered: announcing minimum fuel converts you from an anonymous target into a known problem, and controllers protect known problems. <<if $declared is "late">>Late honesty beat silence by exactly the margin of that final vector.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Minimum fuel (AIM 5-5-15) is an advisory, not a declaration: it buys no priority, only the promise of no unnecessary delay. If the plan needs priority to work, the word is emergency, and 91.3 hands you the airplane and the authority in the same sentence. Better still is the version where neither word is needed because the airplane went where the fuel math was fat instead of where the hangar was. <<if $restumble>>And the panel lesson: "normal" switch positions assume normal fuel. With a dry right tank, X-FEED was the correct landing configuration, whatever the laminated checklist says about ON.<</if>></p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>Minimum fuel is a fact you announce, not a plan you fly to. When the destination needs everything to go right, the destination is wrong.</p>
</div>
