:: End_ELP_Fumes [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: fumes and a tow bar"])>>
The 737 lands. You follow it down final at a respectful distance, the totalizer reading a number you stop looking at, and the touchdown on 26L is the sweetest of your life for reasons nobody else on the frequency knows.

Then, on the turnoff, the left engine stumbles, catches, stumbles again, and dies. The right one, drinking through the crossfeed from the same nearly empty wing, follows it eleven seconds later. The Seneca coasts to a stop with its nose over the taxiway centerline, every annunciator you own lit up, in the sudden ringing silence of an airplane that has spent its last gallon taxiing.

"Six two Charlie, tower, say intentions." You have none. Intentions require fuel. The follow-me truck comes, then the tug, then the paperwork clipboard of the airport operations officer, who is polite in the way of a man writing everything down. Tower asks you to call the facility when you're settled. The call is professional, and long, and ends with a suggestion that you may hear from the Flight Standards District Office, which you do, Monday, in a voicemail with a government cadence to it.

Elena waits through all of it. On the drive home she finally says, "You told me we were fine." She isn't angry. It's worse. She's recalibrating.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>You continued to El Paso on roughly 22 gallons in one wing and told no one anything. The system, believing you were an ordinary airplane, handled you ordinarily: a sequencing vector behind airline traffic that spent your last honest minutes. The airplane ran out of fuel on the taxiway, eleven seconds at a time, in front of the tower, the operations office, and your sister. Five minutes earlier that same arithmetic would have run out on final.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>The load-bearing decision wasn't at the ramp in San Antonio. It was the radio call after the relight, where "back to normal ops" traded safety for image. The attitude underneath it is a quiet blend of invulnerability and reputation-guarding: declaring means explaining, explaining means the story exists. So the story got written by the fuel system instead. Accepting the sequence vector was the same decision made a second time with less fuel. Everything the tower and the FSDO now want to discuss was purchasable, an hour earlier, for two words.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>An IFR pilot who loses and restores an engine has safety-of-flight information, and 91.183(c) expects it on frequency. Minimum fuel (AIM 5-5-15) exists precisely so the sequence bends around the airplane that needs it. Controllers reroute heavies for Senecas that speak up, and the paperwork for an honest precautionary handling is a fraction of the file that gets opened when both props stop on a Class C taxiway. The airplane is undamaged. The margin that produced that outcome was luck, spent at the rate of eleven seconds per engine.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>The system can only protect the airplane you tell it you're flying. Silence bought you a sequence, a tow bar, and a phone number.</p>
</div>
